{"title_page": "Mo Farah", "text_new": "{{redirect|Mohamed Farah|other people of the same name|Mohamed Farah (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|British track and field athlete}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| honorific_prefix = [[Sir]]\n| name = Mohamed Farah\n| honorific_suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} {{post-nominals|OLY|size=100}} {{post-nominals|KT|size=100}}\n| birth_name = Mohamed Muktar Jama Farah\n| image = Mo Farah Doha 2015 (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Farah in 2015\n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| sport = [[Athletics (sport)|Athletics]]/[[track and field|Track]], [[Long-distance running]]\n| country = {{GBR2}}\n| years_active = 1996\u2013present\n| event = [[10,000 meters]], [[5000 meters]], [[1500 meters]], [[Half marathon]], [[Marathon]]\n| club = [[Newham and Essex Beagles]], London<br/>\n| collegeteam =\n| universityteam = [[St Mary's University College, Twickenham|St Mary's University College Twickenham London]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1983|3|23}}<ref name=IAAF>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.org/athletes/biographies/letter=0/athcode=179892/index.html |title=Athletes |website=IAAF.org |date= |accessdate=29 August 2011}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Mogadishu]], [[Somalia]]\n| monuments = [[2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics gold post boxes|Gold Postboxes]] [[Isleworth]], London; [[Teddington]], London<br />[[Madame Tussauds London]] wax sculpture in [[Marylebone]]\n| occupation = [[Running|Runner]]\n| residence = [[London, England|London]], England, [[UK]]<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/athletics/9402196.stm |title=BBC Sport \u2013 Athletics \u2013 Mo Farah changes coach to assist Olympic preparation |website=BBC News |date=18 February 2011 |accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref>\n| spouse = Tania Nell (m. 2010)\n| coach = Charles Van Commenee<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gordonpoole.com/talent/charles-van-commenee/ |title=Charles Van Commenee |website=The Gordon Poole Agency Ltd |accessdate=14 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208101153/http://www.gordonpoole.com/talent/charles-van-commenee/ |archivedate=8 December 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><br />Alan Storey<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/the-world-is-at-farahs-feet-as-guru-helps-him-go-the-distance-1645294.html |title=The world is at Farah's feet as guru helps him go the distance |newspaper=The Independent |date=15 March 2009 |accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref><br />Alan Watkinson<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.education-show.com/Content/Alan-Watkinson-at-The-Education-Show-2015 |title=Alan Watkinson at The Education Show 2015 |website=The Education Show |accessdate=14 December 2015 }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><br />[[Ian Stewart (athlete)|Ian Stewart]] (formerly)\n| website = {{URL|www.mofarah.com}}\n| height = {{T&Fcalc|1.75}}<ref name=sr>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3N84AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT250&lpg=PT250&dq=175+cm+mo+farah&source=bl&ots=7mH4fEVL0Z&sig=sAFErcoIHwsjiRD5N6N8deDHkwo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjdgcKVjtjLAhWJph4KHQ6lAV4Q6AEIRjAL |title=Twin Ambitions \u2013 My Autobiography |first=Mo |last=Farah |page=250 |via=Google Books |date= |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>\n| weight = {{convert|9|st|6|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=sr/>\n| worlds = '''2007 Osaka''' <br> 5000 m, 6th <br> '''2009 Berlin''' <br> 5000 m, 7th <br> '''2011 Daegu''' <br> 10,000 m, {{silver medal}} <br> 5000 m, {{gold medal}} <br> '''2013 Moscow''' <br> 10,000 m, {{gold medal}} <br> 5000 m, {{gold medal}} <br> '''2015 Beijing''' <br> 10,000 m, {{gold medal}} <br> 5000 m, {{gold medal}} <br> '''2017 London''' <br> 10,000 m, {{gold medal}} <br> 5000 m, {{silver medal}}\n| olympics = '''2008 Beijing''' <br> 5000 m, 17th (h) <br> '''2012 London''' <br> 10,000 m, {{gold medal}} <br> 5000 m, {{gold medal}} <br> '''2016 Rio de Janeiro''' <br> 10,000 m, {{gold medal}} <br> 5000 m, {{gold medal}}\n| pb = {{unbulleted list\n|'''Outdoor''' <ref name=\"IAAF-Time\">{{cite web |url=https://www.iaaf.org/athletes/great-britain-ni/mohamed-farah-179892 |website=International Association of Athletics Federations |title=Profile of Mo Farah}}</ref>\n|'''[[800 m]]:''' 1:48.24 ([[Lugano]] 2008)\n|'''[[1500 metres|1500 m]]:''' 3:28.81 '''[[List of European records in athletics|ER]]''' ([[Monaco]] 2013)\n|'''[[mile run|Mile]]:''' 3:56.49 ([[London]]&nbsp;2005)\n|'''[[3000 m]]:''' 7:32.62 '''[[List of British records in athletics|NR]]''' ([[Birmingham, England|Birmingham]] 2016)\n|'''[[Two miles|2-mile]]:''' 8:07.85 '''[[List of European records in athletics|ER]]''' ([[Birmingham, England|Birmingham]] 2014)\n|'''[[5000 metres|5000 m]]:''' 12:53.11 '''[[List of British records in athletics|NR]]''' ([[Monaco]] 2011)\n|'''[[10,000 metres|10,000 m]]:''' 26:46.57 '''[[List of European records in athletics|ER]]''' ([[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]] 2011)\n|'''Indoor''' <ref name=\"IAAF-Time\"/>\n|'''[[3000 m]]:''' 7:34.47{{AthAbbr|i|Indoors}} '''[[List of British records in athletics|NR]]''' ([[Birmingham, England|Birmingham]] 2009)\n|'''[[Two miles|2-mile]]:''' 8:03.40{{AthAbbr|i|Indoors}} '''[[World records in athletics|WR]]''' ([[Birmingham, England|Birmingham]] 2015)\n|'''[[5000 metres|5000 m]]:''' 13:09.16{{AthAbbr|i|Indoors}} '''[[List of European records in athletics|ER]]''' ([[Birmingham, England|Birmingham]] 2017)\n|'''Road''' <ref name=\"IAAF-Time\"/>\n|'''[[10K run|10 km]]:''' 27:44 '''[[List of British records in athletics|NR]]''' ([[London]] 2010)\n|'''[[Half marathon]]:''' 59:07{{AthAbbr|a|aided}} '''[[List of European records in athletics|ER]]''' ([[South&nbsp;Shields]]&nbsp;2019)\n|'''[[Marathon]]:''' 2:05:11 '''[[List of European records in athletics|ER]]''' ([[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]] 2018)\n}}\n| show-medals = no\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]|4|0|0\n|[[IAAF World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]]|6|2|0\n|[[IAAF World Half Marathon Championships|World Half Marathon Championships]]|0|0|1\n|[[European Athletics Championships|European Championships]]|5|1|0\n|[[European Indoor Championships in Athletics|European Indoor Championships]]|2|0|0\n|[[European Cross Country Championships]]|1|3|1\n|[[European Team Championships]]|1|0|0\n|[[European Athletics U23 Championships|European U23 Championships]]|0|3|0\n|'''Total'''|'''19'''|'''9'''|'''2'''\n}}\n{{medal|Sport|Men's [[Sport of athletics|athletics]]}}\n{{medal|Country|{{GBR2}}}}\n{{medal|Comp|[[Athletics at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016&nbsp;Rio&nbsp;de&nbsp;Janeiro]]|[[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]]|[[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]]|[[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Competition|[[IAAF World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2017 World Championships in Athletics|2017 London]]|[[2017 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2015 World Championships in Athletics|2015 Beijing]]|[[2015 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2015 World Championships in Athletics|2015 Beijing]]|[[2015 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2013 World Championships in Athletics|2013 Moscow]]|[[2013 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2013 World Championships in Athletics|2013 Moscow]]|[[2013 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2011 World Championships in Athletics|2011 Daegu]]|[[2011 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Silver|[[2017 World Championships in Athletics|2017 London]]|[[2017 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Silver|[[2011 World Championships in Athletics|2011 Daegu]]|[[2011 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Competition|[[IAAF Diamond League|Diamond League]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2017 IAAF Diamond League|2017 Zurich]]|5000 m}}\n{{medal|Competition|[[IAAF World Half Marathon Championships|World Half Marathon Championships]]}}\n{{medal|Bronze|[[2016 IAAF World Half Marathon Championships|2016 Cardiff]]|Individual}}\n{{medal|Competition|[[European Athletics Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2014 European Athletics Championships|2014 Z\u00fcrich]]|[[2014 European Athletics Championships \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2014 European Athletics Championships|2014 Z\u00fcrich]]|[[2014 European Athletics Championships \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2012 European Athletics Championships|2012 Helsinki]]|[[2012 European Athletics Championships \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2010 European Athletics Championships|2010 Barcelona]]|[[2010 European Athletics Championships \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2010 European Athletics Championships|2010 Barcelona]]|[[2010 European Athletics Championships \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Silver|[[2006 European Athletics Championships|2006 G\u00f6teborg]]|[[2006 European Athletics Championships \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Competition|[[European Indoor Championships in Athletics|European Indoor Championships]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2011 European Athletics Indoor Championships|2011 Paris]]|[[2011 European Athletics Indoor Championships \u2013 Men's 3000 metres|3000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2009 European Indoor Championships in Athletics|2009 Torino]]|[[2009 European Athletics Indoor Championships \u2013 Men's 3000 metres|3000 m]]}}\n{{medal|Competition|[[European Cross Country Championships]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2009 European Team Championships|2009 Leiria]]|5000 m}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[2006 European Cross Country Championships|2006 San Giorgio su Legnano]]|Individual}}\n{{medal|Silver|[[2009 European Cross Country Championships|2009 Dublin]]|Individual}}\n{{medal|Silver|[[2009 European Cross Country Championships|2009 Dublin]]|Team}}\n{{medal|Silver|[[2008 European Cross Country Championships|2008 Brussels]]|Individual}}\n{{medal|Bronze|[[2008 European Cross Country Championships|2008 Brussels]]|Team}}\n{{medal|Competition|[[List of half marathon races|Half Marathon]]}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[Great North Run|2019 Newcastle]]|Individual}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[Great North Run|2018 Newcastle]]|Individual}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[Great North Run|2017 Newcastle]]|Individual}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[Great North Run|2016 Newcastle]]|Individual}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[Great North Run|2015 Newcastle]]|Individual}}\n{{medal|Gold|[[Great North Run|2014 Newcastle]]|Individual}}\n{{medal|Silver|[[Great North Run|2013 Newcastle]]|Individual}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Marathon Majors]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2018 Chicago Marathon|2018 Chicago]] | [[Chicago Marathon|Marathon]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2018 London Marathon|2018 London]] | [[London Marathon|Marathon]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Sir Mohamed Muktar Jama Farah''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|CBE}} {{postnominals|OLY}} (born 23 March 1983) is a British [[Long-distance running|distance runner]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Lindstrom |first=Sieg |url=http://www.britannica.com/biography/Mo-Farah |title=Sir Mo Farah &#124; British athlete |website=Britannica.com |date= |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> The most successful British track athlete in modern Olympic Games history, he is the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012]] and [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Olympic gold medalist]] in both the 5000&nbsp;m and 10,000&nbsp;m. Farah is the second athlete in modern Olympic Games history, after [[Lasse Vir\u00e9n]], to win both the 5000&nbsp;m and 10,000&nbsp;m titles at successive Olympic Games. He also completed the 'distance double' at the [[2013 World Championships in Athletics|2013]] and [[2015 World Championships in Athletics]]. He was the second man in history, after [[Kenenisa Bekele]], to win long-distance doubles at successive Olympics and World Championships, and the first in history to defend both distance titles in both major global competitions \u2013 a feat described as the 'quadruple-double'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/othersport/836564/Mo-Farah-when-running-London-2017-World-Athletic-Championships-start-time-10000m-5000m|title=When is Mo Farah's final race at London 2017? Start time at World Athletics Championships|last=Foster|first=Alice|date=2017-08-12|website=Express.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/figure-skating/summer/2016/athletes/_/athlete/20005 |title=2016 Summer Olympics Bio \u2013 Mo Farah |website=ESPN |accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> Since finishing 2nd in the 10,000 metres at the [[2011 World Championships in Athletics]], Farah had an unbroken streak of ten global final wins (the 5000m in 2011, the 10,000m in 2017 and the double in 2012, 2013, 2015 and 2016). The streak ended in Farah's final championship track race, when he finished second to Ethiopia's [[Muktar Edris]] in the 2017 5000 metres final. In his final track race, the [[2017 IAAF Diamond League|2017 Diamond League Final]] in Zurich in August 2017, Farah gained his revenge, edging out world champion Edris to win his only IAAF Diamond League title at 5000 metres.\n\nOn the track, he mostly competed over [[5000 metres]] and [[10,000 metres]], but has run competitively from [[1500 metres]] to the [[marathon]]. In 2017 he indicated his intention to switch wholly to road racing following victory at his final track race, the [[2017 IAAF Diamond League]] 5000 metres final. His running style has been described as \"bouncy\" and tactical,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/10460879/Coup-for-UK-Athletics-as-Mo-Farah-coach-Alberto-Salazar-agrees-to-help-Britains-middle-and-long-distance-runners.html|title=Coup for UK Athletics as Mo Farah coach Alberto Salazar agrees to help Britain's middle and long-distance runners|last=Hart|first=Simon|date=19 November 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/aug/17/mo-farah-world-championship-wins|title=Mo Farah: 'World championship wins tougher than London 2012'|last=Ingle|first=Sean|date=17 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Observer]]|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> which he has attempted to alter for a more efficient and energy-saving stride pattern, especially in the longer distances.<ref name=\"Mara\">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sport/golf/mo-farah-changing-stride-for-marathon-task-1.1624702|title=Mo Farah changing stride for marathon task|last=Ingle|first=Sean|date=12 December 2013|newspaper=The Irish Times|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Farah runs distance races tactically, a style which is aided by his quick [[sprint (running)|sprint finish]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letsrun.com/news/2013/08/with-best-tactics-and-speed-britains-mo-farah-captures-world-10000m-title/|title=With Best Tactics and Speed, Britain's Mo Farah Captures World 10,000m Title|last=Monti|first=Dave|date=10 August 2013|website=Let's Run|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Mogadishu]], [[Somalia]], to an [[Isaaq]] [[Somali people|Somali]] family from [[Gabiley]], [[Somaliland]], Farah went on to be based in [[London]] and ran for [[Newham and Essex Beagles]] athletics club, training at [[St. Mary's University College (Twickenham)|St Mary's University College, Twickenham]] from 2001 to 2011. Farah is the [[European records in athletics|European record]] holder for the 1500&nbsp;m, 10,000 m, [[half marathon]], [[marathon]], and [[two miles]], the [[British records in athletics|British record]] holder for the 5000 m, the European indoor record holder for 5000 m, the British indoor record in the 3000 m and the current indoor [[List of world records in athletics|world record]] holder for the [[two miles]].\n\nFarah is the most decorated athlete in [[British athletics history]], with ten global titles, and was the first British athlete to win two gold medals at the same world championships, although [[Dame Kelly Holmes]] had achieved the feat at an Olympic Games. His five gold medals at the European Athletics Championships make him the most successful athlete in individual events in the championships' history. He has won the [[European Athlete of the Year Trophy|European Athlete of the Year]] award and the [[BAWA Athlete of the Year|British Athletics Writers Association British Athlete of the Year]] award more than any other athlete, three times and six times respectively. Farah was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in 2013 and was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] by Queen [[Elizabeth II]] in the [[2017 New Year Honours]] for services to athletics.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61803 |supp=y|page=N2 |date=31 December 2016}}\n</ref>\nHe won the 2018 Chicago Marathon in a time of 2:05:11, a European record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://results.chicagomarathon.com/2018/?pid=list|title=Bank of America Chicago Marathon|website=results.chicagomarathon.com|access-date=2018-10-07}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMohamed Muktar Jama Farah was born on 23 March 1983 in [[Mogadishu]], [[Somalia]].<ref>https://www.britannica.com/biography/Mo-Farah</ref> Although Farah's family was originally from [[Gabiley]], they were living in Mogadishu, Somalia as his father was a businessman there. After fleeing from Mogadishu to Gabiley with his family,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/mo-farah-and-me|title=Mo and me|first=Ismail|last=Einashe|publisher=|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref> Farah then spent his early childhood as a refugee in [[Djibouti]] with his twin brother.<ref name=\"Befarggbaifh\">{{cite web |last=Fordyce |first=Tom |title=Ennis, Farah and Rutherford give GB athletics its finest hour |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/19125682 |accessdate=5 August 2012|website=BBC Sport |date=5 August 2012}}</ref> He moved to Britain at the age of eight to join his father, speaking barely a word of English.<ref name=\"Befarggbaifh\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/olympics/athletics/team-gbs-mo-farahs-inspirational-former-pe-teacher-to-cheer-him-at-london-2012-8005373.html |newspaper=The Independent |title=Team GB's Mo Farah's inspirational former PE teacher to cheer him at London 2012 |date=3 August 2012 |first=Mark |last=Blunden}}</ref> His grandfather, Jama, was born in the [[British Somaliland|British protectorate of Somaliland]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Farah |first1=Mo |title=Twin Ambitions \u2013 My Autobiography |date=2013 |page=2}}</ref> His father, Mukhtar Farah, is an IT consultant and a British citizen, who was born in [[London]] and grew up in [[Hounslow]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/london-2012/9452253/London-2012-Olympics-Mo-Farah-wins-gold-medal-in-the-10000-metres-final.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=Adam |last=Lusher |title=London 2012 Olympics: Mo Farah wins gold medal in the 10,000 metres final |date=4 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Ltohaltwtdtmfttgm\">{{cite news |first1=David |last1=Cohen |first2=Simon |last2=Freeman |title=London 2012 Olympics: How a love that went the distance took Mo Farah to the gold medal |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/olympics/athletics/london-2012-olympics-how-a-love-that-went-the-distance-took-mo-farah-to-the-gold-medal-8009426.html |accessdate=15 October 2013 |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=6 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"The Independent\">{{cite news |last=Fahy |first=Dylan |date=13 June 2008 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/brian-viner-interviews-mo-farah-846351.html |title=Brian Viner interviews Mo Farah |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nWhen growing up he got a job at [[McDonald's]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2019/apr/27/mo-farah-my-worst-trait-being-ruthless-q-and-a|title=Mo Farah: \u2018My worst trait? Being ruthless'|last=Greenstreet|first=Rosanna|date=2019-04-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-04-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Farah attended [[Isleworth and Syon School]], and [[Feltham Community College]]. His athletic talent was first identified by [[physical education]] teacher Alan Watkinson.<ref name=FarahStars>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/get_involved/6908213.stm |title=Farah stars, with support |website=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=23 June 2008 |date=26 July 2007 |first=Isaac |last=Fanin}}</ref> Farah's ambition was to become a car mechanic or play as a [[Winger (soccer)|right winger]] for [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]] football club.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Bailey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2013/dec/21/mo-farah-this-much-i-know |title=Mo Farah: 'My secret skill is making animal noises' |newspaper=The Observer |date=21 December 2013 |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> He later joined the Borough of Hounslow Athletics Club in west London.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/mo-farah-how-britains-athletics-hero-escaped-the-chaos-of-somalia-2037996.html |location=London |newspaper=The Independent |first=Cahal |last=Milmo |title=How Britain's athletics hero escaped the chaos of Somalia |date=29 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.omriyadat.com/european-athletics/mo-farah-gold-medal-olympics |title=Farah's golds should not be devalued by Salazar accusations, says Coe |website=Om Riyadat |date=13 September 2016 |accessdate=13 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919010306/http://en.omriyadat.com/european-athletics/mo-farah-gold-medal-olympics |archive-date=19 September 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Junior career==\nFarah represented [[London Borough of Hounslow|Hounslow]] at cross-country in the [[London Youth Games]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londonyouthgames.org/page.asp?section=23&sectionTitle=Hall+of+Fame |title=Hall of Fame |website=London Youth Games.org |accessdate=16 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307230906/http://www.londonyouthgames.org/page.asp?section=23&sectionTitle=Hall+of+Fame |archive-date=7 March 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 1996, at the age of 13, he entered the English schools cross-country and finished ninth. The following year he won the first of five English school titles.<ref name=FarahStars/> Recognising his talent, athletics philanthropist [[Eddie Kulukundis]] paid the legal fees to complete Farah's naturalisation as a British citizen, allowing Farah to travel to competitions without visa issues.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hart |first=Simon |date=11 September 2011 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/athletics/8767684/London-2012-Olympics-Mo-Farahs-rise-to-the-pinnacle-of-his-sport-is-a-quintessential-British-success-story.html |title=London 2012 Olympics: Mo Farah\u2019s rise to the pinnacle of his sport is a quintessential British success story |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=19 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Farah |first=Mo |title=Twin Ambitions - My Autobiography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W9NgPRdHAjUC&pg=PT81&lpg=PT81&dq=mo+farah+kulukundis&source=bl&ots=yu8Gkgm9O4&sig=1r-OELnoCtcPLKM7wldLmQT5eGc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CFQQ6AEwC2oVChMI4fuTxv7lxgIVAZgUCh3PcgVO#v=onepage&q=mo%20farah%20kulukundis&f=false |date=10 October 2013 |publisher=Hodder & Stoughton |isbn=978-1-4447-7959-2 |page=81 |accessdate=19 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nFarah's first major title was in the [[5000 metres]] at the [[2001 European Athletics Junior Championships|European Athletics Junior Championship]] in 2001,<ref name=\"pace\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pacesportsmanagement.com/athlete_profile.asp?id=42 |website=PACE Sports Management |title=FARAH, Mo: Profile |accessdate=23 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723104705/http://www.pacesportsmanagement.com/athlete_profile.asp?id=42 |archivedate=23 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the same year that he began training at [[St Mary's University, Twickenham]]. That year, Farah became one of the first two athletes in the newly formed Endurance Performance Centre at St Mary's. He lived and trained at the College, and took some modules in an access course before becoming a full-time athlete as his career progressed.\n\n==Senior career==\n===2005\u20132008: First titles and personal bests===\n[[File:20081214 mo farah.jpg|thumb|upright|Farah at the [[2008 European Cross Country Championships]].]]\nIn 2005, Farah moved in with Australian [[Craig Mottram]] and a group of Kenyan runners that included 10,000 m world number one [[Micah Kogo]]. \"They sleep, eat, train and rest, that's all they do but as an athlete you have to do all those things. Running with Craig made me feel more positive,\" Farah said. \"If I ever want to be as good as these athletes I've got to work harder. I don't just want to be British number one, I want to be up there with the best.\"<ref name=FarahStars/>\n\nIn July 2006, Farah recorded a time of 13 minutes 9.40 seconds for 5000 m to become Britain's second-fastest runner after [[Dave Moorcroft]]. A month later, Farah won the silver medal in the European Championship 5000m in [[Gothenburg]]. Coaches Alan Storey and [[Mark Rowland]] made sure that Farah remained competitive and a few words from [[Paula Radcliffe]] before the 5000&nbsp;m final inspired Farah. He has stated that: \"She said to me, 'Go out and be brave. Just believe in yourself'.\"<ref name=FarahStars/> In December 2006, Farah won the [[2006 European Cross Country Championships]] in [[San Giorgio su Legnano]], Italy.<ref name=\"BBC-Cross-Country\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/6166845.stm |work=BBC Sport |title=Farah storms to European success |date=10 December 2006}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2007 European Indoor Championships in Athletics|2007 European Indoor Championship]] Farah fell and amid confusion started running in the wrong direction.<ref name=\":0\" /> Farah represented the UK at 5000 m in the [[2007 World Championships in Athletics|2007 World Championships]] in [[Osaka]], Japan. Farah finished sixth in a time of 13:47.54.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://osaka2007.iaaf.org/results/gender=M/discipline=5000/combCode=hash/roundCode=f/result.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026134911/http://osaka2007.iaaf.org/results/gender%3DM/discipline%3D5000/combCode%3Dhash/roundCode%3Df/result.html |archive-date=26 October 2007 |website=[[IAAF]] |title=5000m Results, Osaka 2007 |accessdate=21 August 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/6974721.stm |work=BBC News |title=World Championships 2007 Day Nine: As It Happened |date=2 September 2007 |accessdate=21 August 2016 |first=Sarah |last=Holt}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2008, Farah ran 10,000 m events, which was the fastest UK men's time for almost eight years. However, he was [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres#Heat 2|knocked out]] before the 5000 m final at the [[2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Olympics]] in Beijing.\n\n===2009\u20132010: British records and European champion===\nIn January 2009, Farah set a new British indoor record in the 3000&nbsp;metres, breaking [[John Mayock]]'s record with a time of 7 minutes 40.99 seconds in [[Glasgow]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/7862762.stm |title=Farah breaks 3000m indoor record |website=BBC Sport |date=31 January 2009 |accessdate=3 February 2009}}</ref> A few weeks later, he broke his own record by more than six seconds with a time of 7 minutes 34.47 at the UK Indoor Grand Prix in Birmingham,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/7881862.stm |title=Farah breaks record in Birmingham |website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=21 February 2009 |accessdate=22 February 2009}}</ref> a performance which commentator [[Steve Cram]] called \"the best performance by a male British distance runner for a generation\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Cram |date=24 February 2009 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2009/feb/24/athletics-mo-farah-steve-cram |title=Funny guy Farah is now seriously fast |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> Farah attributed his good form to a spell of winter training at altitude in Ethiopia and Kenya.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/4743383/Mo-Farah-sets-new-3000m-record-on-good-day-for-British-athletes.html |title=Mo Farah beats own record on good day for British athletes |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=21 February 2009}}</ref> In March 2009 he took gold in the 3000&nbsp;m at the [[European Indoor Championships in Athletics|European Indoor Championships]] in Turin, recording a time of 7 minutes 40.17.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/7930271.stm |title=Farah cruises home to 3,000m gold |website=BBC Sport |date=7 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nFarah competed at the [[2009 World Championships in Athletics]]: he was in the leading pack early on in the [[2009 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000 metres race]] and eventually finished seventh \u2013 the best by a European runner. After the championships, he scored a victory in his first road competition over 10&nbsp;miles, winning the [[Great South Run]] in 46:25 to become the third fastest Briton in spite of strong winds.<ref>{{cite web |last=Martin |first=Dave |date=25 October 2009 |url=http://www.iaaf.org/LRR09/news/newsid=54762.html |title=Farah scores tremendous victory while Monteiro destroys opposition in Portsmouth |website=[[IAAF]] |accessdate=25 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nFarah was one of the favourites to upset [[Serhiy Lebid]]'s dominance at the [[2009 European Cross Country Championships]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Wenig |first=Jorg |date=12 December 2009 |url=http://www.iaaf.org/WXC10/news/kind=100/newsid=55107.html |title=Farah: \"I am in better shape than a year ago\" \u2013 Euro Cross Country Championships press conference |website=[[IAAF]] |accessdate=13 December 2009}}</ref> However, Lebid was never in contention as Farah and [[Alemayehu Bezabeh]] were some distance ahead throughout the run. Farah was overtaken by Bezabeh in the latter stages of the race, leaving the Briton with a second consecutive silver medal at the competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.european-athletics.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=8038&Itemid=2 |title=Bezabeh becomes Spain's first champion, Lebid third |website=[[European Athletics]] |date=13 December 2009 |accessdate=13 December 2009 }}{{dead link|date=November 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> He did not manage to attend the medal ceremony, however, as he collapsed immediately after the race and needed medical attention.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/8410713.stm |title=Hayley Yelling clinches shock win as Mo Farah collapses |website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=13 December 2009 |accessdate=12 January 2010}}</ref> After a close third place behind [[Edwin Soi]] at the [[BOclassic]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Diego |last=Sampaolo |date=1 January 2010 |url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/kind=100/newsid=55200.html |title=Three-peat for Soi in Bolzano |website=IAAF |accessdate=12 January 2010}}</ref> Farah competed in the short course race at the [[Great Edinburgh Cross Country]]. He was the favourite to win and surged ahead to build a comfortable lead. However, he appeared tired in the latter stages and finished third behind British runners Ricky Stevenson and Steve Vernon. Farah again required post-race medical attention and subsequent tests revealed he had low levels of iron and magnesium. He was prescribed supplements for the condition and his high altitude training plans in Kenya were unaffected.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/8450770.stm |title=Mo Farah returns to training after medical tests |website=BBC Sport |date=12 January 2010 |accessdate=12 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mo Farah Barcelona 2010.jpg|thumb|left|Farah celebrating winning the [[2010 European Athletics Championships \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 m]] at the [[2010 European Athletics Championships]]]]\nFarah won the 2010 [[London 10,000]] in late May in a time of 27:44, in the process beating 10K world record holder [[Micah Kogo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/8714577.stm |title=Mo Farah sets new British 10,000m road record |website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=31 May 2010 |accessdate=6 June 2010}}</ref> His success continued the following week at the [[European Cup 10000m|European Cup 10,000&nbsp;m]]. There, he improved his track best by nearly 16 seconds, finishing in a time of 27:28.86. Farah won by a margin of over forty seconds ahead of second placed [[Abdellatif Meftah]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Ramsak |first=Bob |date=6 June 2010 |url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/kind=100/newsid=56952.html |title=Farah and Monteiro take European Cup 10,000m victories |website=[[IAAF]] |accessdate=6 June 2010}}</ref> After training in Africa, he returned to Europe for the [[2010 European Athletics Championships]]. He took the 10,000&nbsp;metres gold medal, overtaking [[Ayad Lamdassem]] with two laps to go and finishing the race unpressured in a time of 28:24.99. This was Farah's first major title and also the first European gold medal in the event for Great Britain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/8859274.stm |title=European Athletics 2010: Brit Farah wins 10,000 m gold |website=BBC Sport |date=27 July 2010 |accessdate=31 July 2010}}</ref> He then went on to win the 5000&nbsp;m from [[Jesus Espa\u00f1a]], becoming only the fifth man in the 66-year history of the European Championships to achieve the 5000&nbsp;m/10,000&nbsp;m double, and the first for 20 years, following in the footsteps of the Czech [[Emil Z\u00e1topek]] in 1950, [[Zdzislaw Krzyszkowiak]] of Poland in 1958, Finland's [[Juha Vaatainen]] in 1971 and [[Salvatore Antibo]], of Italy, in 1990.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/7920602/European-Athletics-Championships-2010-Mo-Farah-wins-5000m-gold-for-Britain.html |title=European Athletics Championships 2010: Mo Farah wins 5,000 m gold for Britain |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=31 July 2010 |accessdate=31 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/8874520.stm |title=European Athletics 2010: Farah seals distance double |website=BBC Sport |date=31 July 2010 |accessdate=31 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 August 2010, at a [[IAAF Diamond League|Diamond League]] meeting in [[Z\u00fcrich]], Farah ran 5000&nbsp;m in 12:57.94, breaking [[David Moorcroft]]'s long-standing British record and becoming the first ever British athlete to run under 13 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/7955166/Diamond-League-Mo-Farah-the-first-Briton-to-run-sub-13-seconds.html |title=Diamond League: Mo Farah the first Briton to run sub-13 minutes |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=19 August 2010 |accessdate=16 August 2013 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, Farah was named track-and-field athlete of the year by the British Olympic Association.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/9309720.stm |title=Farah, Adlington and Williams among Olympic awards |date=21 December 2010 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=21 December 2010}}</ref> He closed the year at the [[BOclassic|BO classic]] and just missed out on the 10,000 m title, losing to [[Imane Merga]] in a sprint finish by 0.2&nbsp;seconds.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sampaolo |first=Diego |date=1 January 2011 |url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/kind=100/newsid=58988.html |title=Merga and Cheruiyot take dramatic victories in Bolzano |website=IAAF |accessdate=1 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2011-12: European and British records, and world medals===\n[[File:Mofarahpost.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The post box on London Road, [[Isleworth]], painted in honour of Farah as part of a [[2012 Olympics gold post boxes in the United Kingdom|scheme to celebrate Britain's 2012 Olympic gold medal winners]]]]\n2011 was a successful year for Farah, beginning on 8 January at the [[Great Edinburgh International Cross Country|Edinburgh Cross Country]], where he defeated the top four finishers of that year's [[2010 European Cross Country Championships|European Championships]] to take victory in the long race.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wenig |first=Jorg |date=8 January 2011 |url=http://www.iaaf.org/CROS11/news/newsid=59023.html |title=Kipchoge and Masai prevail in snowy Edinburgh |website=IAAF |accessdate=9 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2011, Farah announced that he would be relocating to [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], Oregon to work with new coach [[Alberto Salazar]], train alongside [[Galen Rupp]], and avoid the attention of the British tabloids.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1293948-british-olympic-hero-mo-farah-epitome-of-clutch-in-winning-5000-and-10000 |title=Mo Farah Becomes British Olympic Hero, Wins 5,000 and 10,000-Meter Double |date=12 August 2012 |website=Bleacher Report Sport |accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref> On 19 February 2011 in Birmingham, England, Farah broke the European 5000&nbsp;m indoor record with a time of 13:10.60, at the same time taking ten seconds off the 29-year-old British indoor record of [[Nick Rose (runner)|Nick Rose]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2011/feb/20/mo-farah-athletic-grand-prix |location=London |newspaper=The Guardian |first=Anna |last=Kessel |title=Mo Farah hits the heights as new methods pay off in Birmingham |date=20 February 2011}}</ref> On 5 March 2011, he won gold in the 3000 metres at the [[2011 European Athletics Indoor Championships|European Indoor Championships]]. On 20 March, Farah also won the [[NYC Half Marathon]] in a time of 1:00:23, a new British record.<ref name=2011_results>{{cite web |title=Farah wins New York half-marathon |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/athletics/sport/story/80657.html |website=ESPN.co.uk |accessdate=20 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.athleticsweekly.com/news/farah-smashes-uk-record-to-win-new-york-half/ |title=Farah smashes UK record to win New York Half |website=Athletics Weekly |date=20 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828065815/http://www.athleticsweekly.com/news/farah-smashes-uk-record-to-win-new-york-half/ |archivedate=28 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He and training partner Galen Rupp had originally planned on running a 10,000&nbsp;m race in New Zealand. However, after the race was cancelled due to the [[2011 Christchurch earthquake|Christchurch earthquake]] and damage done to the track, they entered the half-marathon in New York.\n\nOn 3 June 2011, at a Diamond League meeting in [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]], Oregon, Farah won the [[Prefontaine Classic]]'s 10,000&nbsp;m event in 26:46.57, setting a new British and European record.<ref name=pre10k>{{cite web |first=Jon |last=Mulkeen |date=4 June 2011 |url=http://www.athleticsweekly.com/news/farah-smashes-european-10000m-record-mosop-breaks-distance-world-records/ |title=Farah smashes European 10,000 m record, Mosop breaks distance world records |website=Athletics Weekly |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607035725/http://www.athleticsweekly.com/news/farah-smashes-european-10000m-record-mosop-breaks-distance-world-records |archivedate=7 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 22 July 2011, at a Diamond League meeting in [[Monaco]], he set a new British national record in the 5000&nbsp;m with a time of 12:53.11.<ref name=flotrack.org>{{cite web |url=http://www.flotrack.org/coverage/238944-Monaco-Diamond-League-Herculis-Meeting-International-dAthletisme-2011/video/501535-Mo-Farah-1st-in-5k-and-new-British-Record-125311-Monaco-Diamond-League-2011 |title=Mo Farah 1st in 5k and new British Record 12:53.11 Monaco Diamond League 2011 |website=Flotrack |date=22 July 2011 |accessdate=13 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327061148/http://www.flotrack.org/coverage/238944-Monaco-Diamond-League-Herculis-Meeting-International-dAthletisme-2011/video/501535-Mo-Farah-1st-in-5k-and-new-British-Record-125311-Monaco-Diamond-League-2011 |archivedate=27 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Farah edged out American [[Bernard Lagat]] to win the race.<ref name=flotrack.org/>\n\nIn the [[2011 World Championships in Athletics]] in [[Daegu]], South Korea, Farah made a major breakthrough on the world stage by taking the silver medal in the 10,000 m and then the gold in the 5000 m.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.morethanthegames.co.uk/athletics/0415407-daegu-2011-farah-storms-famous-5000m-gold-world-championships |title=Daegu 2011: Farah storms to famous 5,000m gold at World Championships |website=More than the Games |date=4 September 2011 |accessdate=13 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608055608/http://www.morethanthegames.co.uk/athletics/0415407-daegu-2011-farah-storms-famous-5000m-gold-world-championships |archivedate=8 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He became the first British man to win a World Championships medal over either distance.{{cn|date=December 2019}} Farah had in fact been more strongly favoured to take the 10,000&nbsp;m title, but was narrowly beaten in a last lap sprint by Ethiopian [[Ibrahim Jeilan]]. In the 5000&nbsp;m, he overcame Lagat, beating him into second place. Following the race, [[Dave Moorcroft]], former 5000 metres world record holder, hailed Farah as \"the greatest male distance runner that Britain has ever seen\".<ref>[[Channel 4]] Athletics commentary, Daegu Championships</ref>\n\nAt the European Championships in June 2012, he won the [[2012 European Athletics Championships \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000m]]. This then made Farah the first athlete to win this European title more than once.<ref>{{cite book |title=Guinness World Records 2014 |last=Glenday |first=Craig |publisher=2013 Guinness World Records Limited |year= |isbn=978-1908843-15-9 |location= |page= |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldrec0000unse_r3e7 }}</ref>\n\n===2012: Double Olympic champion===\n[[File:Mofarlonol10m-a.jpg|thumb|right|Farah on the way to his first Olympic gold medal during the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000&nbsp;m]] event at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]]]]\nAt the [[London 2012 Olympics]], on 4 August, Farah won the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000&nbsp;m]] gold in a time of 27:30.42. This was Great Britain's first Olympic gold medal in the 10,000&nbsp;m, and came after two other gold medals for the country in the same athletics session.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fordyce |first=Tom |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18912148 |title=Mo Farah wins Olympic 10,000m gold for Great Britain |website=BBC Sport |date=4 August 2012 |accessdate=13 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812160109/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18912148 |archive-date=12 August 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"cnn_farah\">{{cite news |last=Layden |first=Tim |title=In a Games filled with memorable moments, few resonate like Bolt |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/olympics/2012/writers/tim_layden/08/11/usain-bolt-mo-farah-2012-olympics-track-and-field/index.html |accessdate=13 August 2012 |date=11 August 2012}}</ref> His training partner, [[Galen Rupp]] of the United States, took second place. At the time both runners were a part of the Nike Oregon Project coached by [[Alberto Salazar]]. Farah stated that he would observe his [[Ramadan]] fast later in the year.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Borden |date=1 August 2012 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/01/sports/olympics/ramadan-poses-challenges-for-muslims-at-the-olympics.html |title=Observance of Ramadan Poses Challenges to Muslim Athletes |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> On 11 August 2012, Farah made it a long-distance double, winning the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5000 metres]] in a time of 13:41.66.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fordyce |first=Tom |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18912882 |title=Mo Farah wins men's 5,000m to claim second Olympic gold |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=13 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812052224/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18912882 |archive-date=12 August 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The noise from the crowd in the 5,000 m race was so loud it made the camera shake and distorted the photo-finish image.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/9499185/Olympics-hero-Mo-Farah-aiming-to-break-Steve-Ovetts-34-year-old-British-record-at-Aviva-Birmingham-Grand-Prix.html |location=London |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=Simon |last=Hart |title=Olympics hero Mo Farah aiming to break Steve Ovett's 34-year-old British record at Aviva Birmingham Grand Prix |date=25 August 2012}}</ref> He dedicated the two golds to his twin daughters.\n\nOn 23 August 2012, Farah returned to the track at a Diamond League meet in [[Birmingham]], where he capped off a winning season with another victory over a distance of two miles ({{convert|2|mi|1|abbr=out|disp=output only}}).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/19368887 |title=Mo Farah celebrates two-mile Diamond League victory |website=BBC Sport |date=26 August 2012 |accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n====CBE====\nFollowing his 2012 successes, Farah was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the 2013 New Year Honours for services to athletics.<ref name=\"Lgsztss\">{{London Gazette |issue=60367 |date=29 December 2012 |page=24 |supp=y}}</ref><ref name=Tnyh>{{cite news |url=http://www.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/sites/default/files/resources/NY2013-honours-London-2012.pdf |title=2013 New Year's Honours |accessdate=29 December 2012}}</ref> The move was met with anger by many in the general public, including erstwhile Minister of Sports [[Gerry Sutcliffe]], who felt that Farah instead deserved a higher accolade.<ref name=\"Mntamfak\">{{cite news |title='Mistake' not to award Mo Farah a knighthood |url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2012-12-29/mistake-to-not-award-mo-farah-a-knighthood/ |accessdate=2 January 2013 |newspaper=ITV |date=29 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Momfofnyhswbwik\">{{cite news |last=Moss |first=Vincent |title=Mo-ment of madness: Fury over Farah's New Year Honours snub while bank watchdog is knighted |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/fury-over-mo-farahs-new-1510704 |accessdate=2 January 2013 |newspaper=The Mirror |date=10 August 2013}}</ref> Farah's former physical education teacher Alan Watkinson similarly indicated that he was disappointed that Farah was not knighted and that the decision \"discredits the system although it's still a fantastic achievement for Mo and well deserved.\"<ref name=\"Momfofnyhswbwik\"/> However, deputy Prime Minister [[Nick Clegg]] cited Farah's Olympic double gold win in his 2013 New Year's message and 2012 Autumn conference,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nickclegg.com/nccom_news_details.aspx?title=Nick_Clegg%E2%80%99s_rally_speech_at_Liberal_Democrat_Autumn_Conference&pPK=ccad70de-e202-43a8-8778-27555c5e6503 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20130103045328/http://www.nickclegg.com/nccom_news_details.aspx?title=Nick_Clegg\u2019s_rally_speech_at_Liberal_Democrat_Autumn_Conference&pPK=ccad70de-e202-43a8-8778-27555c5e6503 |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 January 2013 |title=Nick Clegg's rally speech at Liberal Democrat Autumn Conference |website=Nickclegg.com |date=22 September 2012 |accessdate=16 August 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/latest_news_detail.aspx?title=Nick_Clegg%27s_New_Year_Message_2013&pPK=ca90b839-93d0-4468-a0e9-b0024b784efd |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130423205535/http://www.libdems.org.uk/latest_news_detail.aspx?title=Nick_Clegg's_New_Year_Message_2013&pPK=ca90b839-93d0-4468-a0e9-b0024b784efd |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 April 2013 |title=Nick Clegg's New Year Message 2013 |website=Libdems.org.uk |date=28 December 2012 |accessdate=16 August 2013 }}</ref> and [[David Cameron]] on August 2013 expressed support for a knighthood for Mo Farah.<ref>{{cite news |first=Natasha |last=Culzac |url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/08/18/david-cameron-warmly-welcomes-knighthood-for-olympic-great-mo-farah-3928328/ |title=Mo Farah: David Cameron backs calls to give Olympic gold medallist a knighthood |newspaper=Metro News |date=18 August 2013 |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2013: 1500 m record and world medals===\nOn 19 July 2013, at the [[Herculis]] meeting in Monaco, Farah broke the [[List of European records in athletics|European 1500 m record]] with a time of 3:28.81. The feat meant that he was the [[1500 metres#Men|sixth fastest man ever]] over the distance, overtaking [[Steve Cram]]'s 28-year-old [[British records in athletics|British record]] and Ferm\u00edn Cacho's 16-year-old European record.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lewis |first=Aimee |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/23385989 |title=Mo Farah breaks Steve Cram's 28-year British 1500m record |website=BBC Sport |date=19 July 2013 |accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref> It also made Farah the seventh man, behind [[Sa\u00efd Aouita]], [[Daniel Komen]], [[Ali Sa\u00efdi-Sief]], [[Hicham El Guerrouj]], [[Augustine Kiprono Choge]] and [[Bernard Lagat]] to break both the 3:30 barrier in the 1500 metres and the 13-minute barrier in the 5000 metres, as well as the only athlete in history to run sub 3:30, sub 13-minute and sub 27-minute for 1500 metres, 5000 metres and 10,000 metres respectively. Additionally, he has a sub 1 hour run in the half-marathon.\n[[File:Mofarahannivgames4.jpg|thumb|right|Farah during his gold medal victory in the men's 3,000 metres event at the [[London Grand Prix|2013 London Grand Prix]].]]\nThe following month, Farah won the London Diamond League Anniversary Games' 3000 metres event in a time of seven minutes and 36.85 seconds.<ref name=Dlspwilamfwtaag>{{cite news |title=Diamond League: Sally Pearson wins in London as Mo Farah wins 3000m at Anniversary Games |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-07-28/pearson-wins-as-farah-delights-london-again/4848268 |accessdate=29 July 2013 |newspaper=ABC News |date=28 July 2013}}</ref> He twice broke the national record in the half-marathon, first on 24 February in New Orleans, then broke his own record on 15 September in the [[BUPA]] [[Great North Run]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nOn 10 August 2013, Farah stayed in front of Ibrahim Jeilan to win the [[2013 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000 m]] event at the [[2013 World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]] in Moscow. The victory was his fourth global title.<ref name=fourth/> On 16 August 2013, Farah won the [[2013 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5,000 m]] event, in the process becoming double world and Olympic champion.<ref name=\"Jsmfwfgtbdwaoc\">{{cite news |last=Steinberg |first=Jacob |title=Mo Farah wins 5,000m gold to become double World and double Olympic champion |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/aug/16/mo-farah-world-athletics-championships-5000m-live |accessdate=16 August 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=16 August 2013}}</ref> After this victory, BBC commentator [[Brendan Foster]] and [[Sebastian Coe]] called Farah 'Britain's greatest ever athlete'.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/feature/54 |title=Farah takes the distance double to rise amongst the greats |website=IAAF.org |date=17 August 2013 |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> Farah became only the second man in history to win long-distance titles at successive editions of the Olympics and World Championships, after [[Kenenisa Bekele]]'s 2008\u201309 feat.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/23722814 |title=Mo Farah wins 5,000m gold at World Athletics 2013 |last=Lewis |first=Aimee |website=BBC Sport |date=16 September 2013 |accessdate=16 September 2013}}</ref> He was the first British athlete to win two individual gold medals at a World Championships.<ref name=fourth>{{cite news |last=Morrison |first=Jonathan |title=Mo Farah wins 10,000 metres and fourth world title |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/sport/athletics/article3839547.ece |accessdate=10 August 2013 |newspaper=The Times |date=10 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Black |first=Dan |url=http://www.pendletoday.co.uk/news/columnists/there-s-a-catalogue-of-sport-to-look-forward-to-in-2014-1-6354371 |title=There's a catalogue of sport to look forward to in 2014! |newspaper=Pendle Today |date=8 January 2014 |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/28072010/58/farah-seals-historic-gold-britain.html |title=Farah seals historic gold for Britain |website=Yahoo! Eurosport |date= |accessdate=29 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, Farah was the second favourite, behind Wimbledon tennis champion [[Andy Murray]], to become the BBC Sports Personality of the Year. When he was asked what drove him to keep pushing back the boundaries of athletic accomplishment, he noted sprinter [[Usain Bolt]]'s record breaking streak as a motivating example of what is possible for all dedicated athletes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Spink |first=Alex |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/other-sports/athletics/bbc-sports-personality-year-mo-2915905#.UtpWuDDFKIU |title=BBC Sports Personality of the Year: Mo Farah not expecting to win despite historic 2013 |newspaper=The Mirror |date=11 December 2013 |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nFarah was a finalist for the 2013 IAAF World Athlete of the year award. In preparation for his marathon debut, he also extended his training schedule to 120 miles a week.<ref name=\"Mara\"/>\n\n===2014: Double gold in Z\u00fcrich===\n[[File:5000m men final European Athletics Championships Z\u00fcrich 2014.JPG|thumb|right|Farah on the way to victory in the 5000m men final of the [[2014 European Athletics Championships]].]]\nFarah began 2014 preparing for the year's [[2014 London Marathon|London Marathon]], his first such run. He described running the event as a longstanding ambition of his, particularly to do so in London.<ref>{{cite news |first=Guy |last=Aspin |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/more-sport/athletics/mo-farah-london-marathon-a-huge-test-1-3268663 |title=Mo Farah: London Marathon a huge test |newspaper=The Scotsman |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> Farah finished in eighth place in a time of 2:08.21. This was outside [[Steve Jones (athlete)|Steve Jones]]' GB record, but set a new English national record.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/27009201 |title=Mo Farah finishes eighth on full London Marathon debut |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=13 April 2014 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nFarah was due to compete at the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]] in Glasgow. However, he withdrew due to illness from a stomach ailment and an infection caused from having a tooth removed.<ref name=\"Mfwathabc\">{{cite web |title=Mo Farah was airlifted to hospital after bathroom collapse |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/28748841 |accessdate=19 August 2014 |website=BBC Sport |date=12 August 2014}}</ref> Farah later appeared in Z\u00fcrich at the [[2014 European Athletics Championships]]. He successfully defended his 5000 m title and won a gold in the 10,000 m, thus completing another major championship double.<ref name=\"Mfwftclddaec\">{{cite news|last1=Casert|first1=Raf |title=Mo Farah wins 5k to clinch long distance double at European Championships |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/sports/mo-farah-wins-5k-to-clinch-long-distance-double-at-european-championships-1.1963393 |accessdate=19 August 2014 |agency=Associated Press |website=CTV News |date=17 August 2014}}</ref> This made him the most successful individual in the history of the European Athletics Championships, with five titles to his name.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/28828217 |title=European championships: Mo Farah wins 5000m and record fifth gold |date=17 August 2014 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 September 2014, Farah competed in the [[Great North Run]], a British half marathon. He won the race with a personal best time of 1:00:00, exactly 1&nbsp;hour.<ref>{{cite web |title=Great North Run 2014: Mo Farah claims first victory |website=BBC Sport |date=7 September 2014 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/29074934 |accessdate=7 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2015: World and European records===\nOn 21 February 2015, Farah broke the indoor [[Two miles|two-mile]] world record at the [[Birmingham Indoor Grand Prix]]. He ran an 8:03.4 to break [[Kenenisa Bekele]]'s record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mo Farah breaks indoor two-mile world record in Birmingham |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/athletics/31569286 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March 2015, Farah broke the European record for half marathon in [[Lisbon]]. He ran a time of 59 minutes, 32 seconds, 20 seconds, surpassing the record set 14 years previously by Spain's [[Fabi\u00e1n Roncero]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/32008651 |title=Mo Farah breaks European half marathon record in Lisbon win |website=BBC Sport |date=22 March 2015 |accessdate=7 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe repeated his long-distance gold medal double at the [[2015 World Championships in Athletics]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Sean |last=Ingle |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/dec/27/memorable-moments-2013-mo-farah-double-worlds |title=Memorable moments 2013: Mo Farah seals double-double at Moscow worlds |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 December 2013 |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> His win in the 10,000m made him the oldest World Championship winner in that event, at age 32.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.letsrun.com/news/2015/08/six-in-a-row-for-mo-kenyan-team-tactics-not-enough-to-stop-the-invincible-mo-farah-in-mens-10000/ |title=American Galen Rupp Finishes 5th in 27:08.91 \u2013 4th fastest American 10,000 in History |website=LetsRun.com |date=22 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2016: Double-Double Olympic Golds at Rio===\nOn 26 March, Farah received a bronze medal in the [[2016 IAAF World Half Marathon Championships]] in [[Cardiff]], finishing in 59:59, less than one second ahead of [[Abayneh Ayele]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iaaf.org/competitions/iaaf-world-half-marathon-championships/iaafcardiff-university-world-half-marathon-ch-5614/news/feature/men/half-marathon |title=In victory and defeat, Kamworor and Farah now shift focus to Rio rematch |website=IAAF.org |date=28 March 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Young |first=Dennis |url=http://www.flotrack.org/article/40577-kenyan-duo-clobber-mo-farah-as-kamworor-repeats-at-world-half |title=Kenyan Duo Clobber Mo Farah As Kamworor Repeats at World Half |website=Flotrack.org |date=26 March 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref> On 20 February, Farah won the Glasgow Indoor Grand Prix 3000m event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.iaaf.org/results/iaaf-world-indoor-tour/2016/glasgow-indoor-grand-prix-5853/men/3000-metres/final/result#resultheader |title=3000 Metres Result &#124; Glasgow Indoor Grand Prix |website=IAAF.org |date=20 February 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref> On 5 June 2016, Farah broke the 34-year-old British 3000 metre record set by Moorcroft by winning the Diamond League in [[Birmingham]], a win he dedicated to the recently deceased boxer [[Muhammad Ali]].<ref>{{cite news |agency=Press Association |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/mo-farah-breaks-34yearold-british-3000m-record-and-dedicates-victory-to-hero-muhammad-ali-a3264121.html |title=Mo Farah breaks 34-year-old British 3,000m record and dedicates victory to 'hero' Muhammad Ali |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=5 June 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> In July 2016 Farah set the concurrent world-leading time in the 5000m in winning the Diamond League in London.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://olympics.cbc.ca/news/article/diamond-league-farah-proves-ready-for-rio.html |title=Road to the Olympic Games |website=CBC Sports |date= |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref> He won the 10,000m at the Diamond League in [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]], in a time of 26:53.71 which remained the second-fastest time in the world of the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.iaaf.org/news/iaaf-news/2016-world-athlete-of-the-year-mens-finalists |title=A closer look at the 2016 World Athlete of the Year men's finalists |website=IAAF.org |date= |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 August, Farah won a gold medal in the [[10,000 metres]] at the [[Rio Olympics]], making it the first time a Briton had won three athletic gold Olympic medals.<ref>{{cite web |last=Etchells |first=Daniel |url=http://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1042688/farah-and-beitia-crowned-european-athletes-of-the-year |title=Farah and Beitia crowned European athletes of the year |website=Insidethegames.biz |date=15 October 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref> After being accidentally clipped on the back of the heel by American [[Galen Rupp]] on the 10th lap he fell,<ref name=\"MoFarahFalls\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/14/sports/olympics/mo-farah-men-10k-result.html?_r=0 |title=Mo Farah Falls but Hardly Misses a Step in 10,000-Meter Victory |date=13 August 2016 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=14 August 2016}}</ref> but went on to win gold with the time of 27:05.17. Rupp slowed after Farah's fall to check his condition and finished in 5th place with a time of 27:08.92. In the final lap Farah battled [[Paul Tanui]], who took the lead with 300 metres remaining. Farah edged him out with 100 metres to go. Tanui finished in second place with a time of 27:05.64.<ref name=\"MoFarahFalls\"/>\n\nOn 20 August, Farah went on to win a second gold medal in the [[5,000 metres]] at the Rio Olympics. Coming into the 31st Olympiad, Farah was trying to win gold medals in the 10,000 metres and 5,000 metres to double his success from the [[London Olympics]]. Farah held off the lead he had set and finished with a time of 13.03.30, making it only the second time someone has retained the 5000m and 10,000m Olympic titles, after [[Lasse Vir\u00e9n]] of Finland in 1972 and 1976.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/aug/20/mo-farah-gold-medal-5000m-double-double-history |title=Magical Mo Farah bags another Olympic gold and earns his place in history |date=22 August 2016 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=22 August 2016}}</ref> In September 2016, he won the [[Great North Run]] for a record third consecutive year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-37328765 |title=Great North Run 2016: Mo Farah wins third time in a row |website=BBC News |date= |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he was the fastest person from the European [[continent]] over two [[Middle-distance running|middle distance]] events and three [[Long-distance running|long-distance]] events; the 1500 metres, 3000 metres, 5000 metres, 10,000 metres and the half-marathon respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.insidethegames.biz/index.php/articles/1042685/european-athletics-convention-golden-tracks-awards-ceremony |title=European Athletics Convention: Golden Tracks awards ceremony |website=Insidethegames.biz |date=15 October 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref> His ninth global title, the 5000m in Rio, made him surpass [[Kenenisa Bekele]] as the most frequent winner of gold in history for major long-distance events. He remained unbeaten in 2016 in the 3000m as well as in six races over the 10,000m and 5,000m distances.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/news/20161109/bolt-thompson-among-iaaf-athlete-year-finalists |title=Bolt, Thompson among IAAF Athlete of the Year finalists |newspaper=Jamaica Gleaner |date=9 November 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2017: Tenth world title and track retirement===\nFarah announced that he would switch from track events to the [[marathon]] after the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/athletics/40756958 |title=Mo Farah set for final track appearance in Zurich after World Championships |website=BBC Sport |date=28 July 2017}}</ref> He won the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 10,000 metres|10,000m event]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/sport/mo-farah-wins-tenth-successive-global-title-at-world-championships/|title=Mo Farah wins tenth successive global title in men\u2019s 10,000m at World Championships|last=Lowell|first=Hugo|date=2017-08-04|website=inews.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref> and came 2nd in the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|5,000m]] event after Ethiopia's [[Muktar Edris]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/40833730 |title=World Championships 2017: Mo Farah defends his 10,000m title in London |date=4 August 2017 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/40913661 |title=World Championships 2017: Mo Farah misses out on fifth consecutive distance double |date=12 August 2017 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nFarah won his final two track events, in the Diamond league, in Birmingham and Zurich.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/40993606 |title=Mo Farah wins final race in Britain at Birmingham Diamond League meeting |date=20 August 2017 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/41041891 |title=Mo Farah wins his final track race in Zurich Diamond League event |date=24 August 2017 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref> On 24 August 2017, he won his final 5,000m in the Diamond league, finishing in 13:06.05, in a final sprint against [[Paul Chelimo]] and [[Muktar Edris]] just behind in 13:06.09.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.letsrun.com/news/2017/08/full-results-2017-weltklasse-zurich-diamond-league |title=Full Results 2017 Weltklasse Zurich Diamond League |date=24 August 2017 |website=LetsRun.com |accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2017, Farah again reiterated his decision to move to the marathon full-time, and caused headlines when he announced after running his last 10,000m race on British soil at the Muller Grand Prix in Birmingham that he would never again run in a GB vest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/sport/mo-farah-insists-will-never-compete-british-vest/|title=Mo Farah insists he will never again compete in British vest|last=Lowell|first=Hugo|date=2017-08-20|website=inews.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 September 2017, Farah won the [[Great North Run]] for a record fourth consecutive time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/41218466 |title=Great North Run: Mo Farah wins record fourth successive title |date=10 September 2017 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref> He finished in 1:00:06, 6 seconds ahead of [[Jake Robertson]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.letsrun.com/news/2017/09/2017-great-north-run-results/ |title=2017 Great North Run Results |date=11 September 2017 |website=LetsRun.com |accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 October, Farah split from [[Alberto Salazar]] in order to be coached by [[Gary Lough]], husband and former coach of [[Paula Radcliffe]]. Salazar stated that the split was mutual and he would be happy to advise Farah in the future.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/41811637 |title=Mo Farah splits from coach Alberto Salazar and will return to Britain |date=31 October 2017 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Since 2018: full-time marathon runner===\nIn March 2018, in preparation for the London Marathon, Farah won the inaugural London Big Half Marathon, his first race in six months.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/mar/04/mo-farah-wins-big-half-marathon</ref><ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/athletics/2018/03/04/mo-farah-wins-inaugural-big-half-preparation-london-marathon/</ref> On 22 April 2018, Farah came third in the [[2018 London Marathon|London Marathon]] in a time of 2:06:22, comfortably beating the British record of 2:07:13 set by [[Steve Jones (runner)|Steve Jones]] in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/queen-kick-starts-london-marathon-from-windsor-as-sir-mo-farah-eyes-british-record-11342224|title=Sir Mo Farah smashes British record at hottest ever London Marathon|publisher=|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/athletics/2018/04/22/london-marathon-2018-results-winners-latest-news-live-updates/|title=London Marathon 2018 live race updates: Mo Farah finishes third in British record time|first1=Sam|last1=Dean|first2=J. J.|last2=Bull|date=22 April 2018|publisher=|accessdate=22 April 2018|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> On 9 September 2018 Farah won the Great North Run for a record-extending 5th consecutive time.<ref name=moFar2018>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/45464219 | title = Great North Run 2018: Mo Farah wins for record fifth time | date = 9 September 2018 | website = [[BBC News]] | access-date = 9 September 2018 }}</ref> At the [[2018 Chicago Marathon|Chicago Marathon]] Farah claimed his inaugural gold medal in the marathon distance<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/45778829</ref> and in the process set a new European record of 2 hours 5 minutes and 11 seconds, an improvement by 37 seconds.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mo Farah wins first marathon title with dramatic victory in Chicago |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/oct/07/mo-farah-first-marathon-title-chicago |website=The Guardian |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019: planning a track return ===\n[[File:Mo Farah, Bashir Abdi and Daniel Wanjiru, 2019 London Half Marathon, 10 March 2019.jpg|thumb|Mo Farah (left), [[Bashir Abdi]] and [[Daniel Wanjiru]] compete in the 2019 London Half Marathon - finishing in that order.]]\nIn February 2019, Farah announced he planned to run again in the London Big Half Marathon in March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.athleticsweekly.com/event-news/london-winners-face-mo-farah-at-big-half-1039920484/|title=London winners face Mo Farah at Big Half|date=2019-02-07|website=Athletics Weekly|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> In an interview, he also stated that he is considering competing in the [[Tokyo]] [[Olympic Games|Olympics]] in 2020, which, if confirmed, would mark his fourth Olympic games. As well as stating that this would depend on whether his wife and kids \"let him\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-46279538/mo-farah-tokyo-2020-is-on-the-cards|title=Farah: 2020 is on the cards|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> he reflected on his track retirement, saying:<blockquote>\u201cI was honest and said I was done with the track but part of me missed it. I feel like I can still win medals and do as well as I have over the years.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/nov/20/mo-farah-to-run-2019-london-marathon-2020-olympics|title=Mo Farah to run 2019 London marathon but leaves door open for track return in Tokyo|last=Ingle|first=Sean|date=2018-11-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-02-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref></blockquote>He has also confirmed that he may run in the 10,000 metres at the [[IAAF World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]] in [[Doha]] in late 2019, although this would depend on the result of the 2019 Big Half Marathon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/more-sports/athletics/news/29877/11542127/sir-mo-farah-considering-track-return-ahead-of-2020-olympics|title=Sir Mo Farah considering track return ahead of 2020 Olympics|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> This possibility was later confirmed by Neil Black, performance director of [[UK Athletics|British Athletics]], who has said that Farah had received financial backing from the [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|National Lottery]] in anticipation for both his participation in the Championships, as well as for the Tokyo Olympics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/mo-farah-gets-financial-backing-ahead-of-world-championships-in-qatar-a3988851.html|title=Farah gets financial backing ahead of World Championships in Qatar|date=2018-11-13|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March 2019, Farah won his second London Big Half Marathon, and again hinted at running the 10,000m at the [[2019 World Athletics Championships|World Championships in October 2019]].<ref name=\"BBC-10Mar2019\">{{cite news |title=London Big Half Marathon |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/47513523 |accessdate=10 March 2019 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=10 March 2019}}</ref> In April, Farah finished in 5th place in the [[2019 London Marathon]] in 2:05:39.\n\nOn 8 September 2019, Farah won the 2019 [[Great North Run]] for a record 6th consecutive time in a new Personal best of 59:07.<ref name=\"GNR 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/49625993|title=Great North Run: Mo Farah wins record sixth straight title|date=8 September 2019|website=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 November 2019, Farah announced via his YouTube channel, his plan to return to the track to defend his 10,000m olympic title at the Tokyo 2020 Olympic games. Farah stated he would put his marathon career on hold while he returned to track oriented training.\n\n==\"Mobot\"==\n[[File:Mofarahannivgames1.JPG|thumb|right|Mo Farah completing his \"Mobot\" signature pose at the [[London Grand Prix|2013 London Anniversary Games]].]]\nFarah often marks victories with a celebration dance known as the \"Mobot\". He adopted the move following a television appearance in May 2012 opposite sports presenter [[Clare Balding]], on the panel game show ''[[A League of Their Own (UK game show)|A League of Their Own]]''. The host [[James Corden]] suggested to the panelists that they should think of a new dance to mark Farah's winning celebration, and Balding subsequently came up with the \"''M''\" gesture called \"Mobot\". At its inaugural demonstration, she indicated that the part of the move intended to represent the \"M\" in \"Mo\" was inspired by the dance to \"[[Y.M.C.A. (song)|YMCA]]\", a popular song by the [[Village People]]. Corden himself then named it as the \"Mobot\".<ref name=\"Tmfmdibcb\">{{cite news |title=Mo Farah's Mobot dance invented by Clare Balding |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/news/9470549/Mo-Farahs-Mobot-dance-invented-by-Clare-Balding.html |accessdate=13 August 2012 |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=12 August 2012|location=London}}</ref> A robot was named \"Mobot\" at a university research exhibition, in honour of Farah's celebration.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/Meet-real-Mobot-ndash-track-champ-s-simply/story-16909443-detail/story.html |title=Meet the real 'Mobot' \u2013 track champ who's simply electric |website=This is Plymouth.co.uk |date=15 September 2012 |accessdate=16 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205010546/http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/Meet-real-Mobot-ndash-track-champ-s-simply/story-16909443-detail/story.html |archivedate=5 December 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Farah has since used the pose as part of a charity to raise funds for his foundation. [[Virgin Media]] has promised to donate \u00a32 for every [[YouTube]] video that is uploaded with someone doing the mobot.<ref>{{cite web |last=Miles |first=Stuart |url=http://www.pocket-lint.com/news/48541/do-the-mobot-internet-sensation |title=Could Mo Farah's Do the Mobot be the new Gangnam Style? Internet sensation in the making |website=Pocket-lint.com |date=26 November 2012 |accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref> Farah often uses the sign-off ''Shabba'' in online postings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/olympic-hero-mo-farah-confirmed-3532797 |title=Olympic hero Mo Farah has confirmed he will take part in this year's Commonwealth Games in Glasgow |newspaper=Daily Record |date=12 May 2014 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Family and interests===\nFarah has a twin brother, Hassan, who lives in [[Somaliland]]. They were separated at eight years old, when Mo, his two younger brothers, and his mother joined their father, who had been working and studying in the UK. Hassan, however, was unwell and unable to travel, so stayed behind with family in Djibouti. When Farah's father returned to collect Hassan, the family he was living with had moved and could not be found. Farah and his twin ended up being separated for twelve years. Hassan is now a telecoms engineer with a wife and five children. Farah has a third younger brother, who was also born after the family's move to London.<ref>{{cite news |last=Farah |first=Mo |date=6 October 2013 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/10359526/Mo-Farah-I-missed-my-twin-brother-Hassan-so-much-during-our-12-year-separation.html |title=Mo Farah: I missed my twin brother Hassan so much during our 12-year separation |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> Farah's cousin, [[Yonis Farah|Yonis]], plays football internationally for [[Somalia national football team|Somalia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.echo-news.co.uk/sport/14685897.southend-uniteds-yonis-farah-inspired-by-cousin-mo-farahs-olympic-gold-medal-display/|title=Southend United's Yonis Farah inspired by cousin Mo Farah's Olympic gold medal display|publisher=Basildon Echo|date=16 August 2016|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2010, Farah married his longtime girlfriend Tania Nell in [[Richmond, London|Richmond]], London. Other athletes at the wedding included [[Paula Radcliffe]], [[Steve Cram]], [[Hayley Yelling]], [[Jo Pavey]], [[Mustafa Mohamed]] and [[Scott Overall]], who was an usher.<ref>{{cite web |author=aliceD |url=http://www.all-athletics.com/en-us/2010-04-04/mo-farahs-wedding |title=Mo Farah's wedding |website=All-Athletics.com |date=4 April 2010 |accessdate=29 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Anna |last=Kessell |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/11/london-2012-scott-overall-mo-farah?newsfeed=true |title=London 2012: Marathon runner Scott Overall inspired by Mo Farah |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 August 2012 |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref> Farah has a stepdaughter named Rihanna from this relationship.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite web |last=Orstein |first=David |title=BBC Sports Personality of the Year 2011 as it happened |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tv_and_radio/sports_personality_of_the_year/9665667.stm |accessdate=15 July 2012 |website=BBC News |date=22 December 2011}}</ref> He and his wife have twin daughters called Aisha and Amani, born in August 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Olympic hero Mo Farah father of twin girls |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-19379381 |website=BBC News |date=25 August 2012 |accessdate=28 August 2012}}</ref> In 2015, Farah and Nell had a son called Hussein.\n\nFrom 2011 to 2017, Farah lived with his family in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], Oregon, so that he could train full-time with the [[Nike Oregon Project]].<ref name=\"Ohmfatbteibtsm\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/olympic-hero-mo-farah-applies-3014093 |title=Olympic hero Mo Farah applies to be tax exile in bid to save millions\n|date=12 January 2014 |newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]] |accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref> At the end of 2017 he cut ties with his coach [[Alberto Salazar]] and decided to return to London. His statement said \"Tania and I realised how much we have missed spending time with our friends and family - and the kids are so happy here, too. We want the kids to grow up in the UK. It's the right thing to do for my family.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/athletics/2017/10/30/mo-farah-splits-coach-alberto-salazar-ahead-move-back-london/ Mo Farah splits with coach Alberto Salazar ahead of move back to London]. The Telegraph.</ref>\n\nFarah is a [[Muslim]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/london-2012/9452253/London-2012-Olympics-Mo-Farah-wins-gold-medal-in-the-10000-metres-final.html |location=London |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |title=London 2012 Olympics: Mo Farah wins gold medal in the 10,000 metres final |date=4 August 2012 |first=Adam |last=Lusher}}</ref> and is an active supporter of the [[Muslim Writers Awards]].<ref name=\"Muwraw\">{{cite web |title=Sports stars Mo Farah and Amir Khan join list of supporters |url=http://muslimwritersawards.org.uk/news-and-events/news/sports-stars-mo-farah-and-amir-khan-join-list-supporters |website=[[Muslim Writers Awards]] |accessdate=17 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701231404/http://muslimwritersawards.org.uk/news-and-events/news/sports-stars-mo-farah-and-amir-khan-join-list-supporters |archivedate=1 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Islam]] is an important part of his preparation: \"I normally pray before a race, I read [[dua]] [Islamic prayers or invocations], think about how hard I've worked and just go for it.\" He notes that \"the [[Qur'an]] says that you must work hard in whatever you do, so I work hard in training and that's got a lot to do with being successful. [It] doesn't just come overnight, you've got to train for it and believe in yourself; that's the most important thing.\"<ref name=\"Milmo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/olympics/news/mo-farah-seeks-a-peaceful-haven-as-he-prepares-for-second-date-with-olympic-destiny-8031603.html |title=Mo Farah seeks a peaceful haven as he prepares for second date with Olympic destiny |last=Milmo |first=Cahil |newspaper=The Independent |date=10 August 2012 |accessdate=10 August 2013|location=London}}</ref> An [[Royal Islamic Strategic Studies Centre|RISSC]] publication named Farah as among the [[500 most influential Muslims]] in the world in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/news-releases/influencing-muslims-the-500-most-influential-muslims-234033281.html |title=Influencing Muslims: The 500 Most Influential Muslims |website=PR Newswire |accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nFarah is also a fan of [[Arsenal F.C.]], and has trained with its first team squad.<ref name=\"Afow\">{{cite news |url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/tv-online-mo-farah-at-emirates-stadium |location=London |website=Arsenal FC Official website |title=TV Online: Mo Farah at Emirates Stadium |date=1 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100904175628/http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/tv-online-mo-farah-at-emirates-stadium |archivedate=4 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Mfcawshafc\">{{cite news |url=http://metro.co.uk/2012/09/04/mo-farah-calls-on-arsene-wenger-to-sign-him-up-as-arsenal-fitness-coach-564720/ |title=Mo Farah calls on Arsene Wenger to sign him up as Arsenal fitness coach |newspaper=Metro |date=4 September 2012 |accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> He has indicated a desire to become a fitness coach at the [[Emirates Stadium]] in [[Holloway, London|Holloway]]<ref>{{cite web |first=Sarad |last=Shrestha |url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/uk-olympic-hero-mo-farah-eyes-arsenal-fitness-job-4148447 |title=UK Olympic hero Mo Farah eyes Arsenal fitness job |website=Tribal Football |date=27 September 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref> once he retires so as to improve its conditioning record.<ref name=\"Mfcawshafc\"/> In October 2013, he launched a book titled ''Mo Farah, Twin Ambitions: My autobiography'' in [[Canary Wharf]], London.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/10361764/Mo-Farah-This-is-my-moment-my-race-I-will-not-be-beaten-at-the-London-Olympic-Games.html |title=Mo Farah: This is my moment, my race \u2013 I will not be beaten at the London Olympic Games |first=Mo |last=Farah |date=7 October 2013 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nFarah has a large following on social media. This includes roughly 1.5&nbsp;million followers on [[Twitter]] and 1.1&nbsp;million on [[Facebook]]. In 2013, he was the top-ranked query for a sportsperson on the search engine Microsoft UK [[Bing (search engine)|Bing]] who was not a footballer.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/justin-bieber-is-bings-most-searched-for-person-of-2013-29801984.html |title=Justin Bieber is Bing's most searched for person of 2013 |date=2 December 2013 |newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] |accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\n[[File:Mo farah2.jpg|thumb|right|Farah at the [[London Youth Games|2010 London Youth Games]] Hall of Fame and Awards Evening.]]\nFarah is additionally involved in various philanthropic initiatives, launching the Mo Farah Foundation after a trip to Somalia in 2011.<ref name=\"Usborne\">{{cite news |last=Usborne |first=Simon |title=Mo Farah: Young man in a hurry |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/olympics/athletics/mo-farah-young-man-in-a-hurry-8007127.html |accessdate=16 August 2012 |newspaper=The Independent |date=4 August 2012|location=London}}</ref> The following year, he participated in ITV's ''[[The Cube (game show)|The Cube]]'' and won \u00a3250,000 for his foundation, becoming the only person to win the top prize on the show.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialphillipschofield.com/news/2012/02/01/mo-farah-has-become-the-first-person-to-beat-the-cube/5981 |title=Mo Farah has become the first person to beat The Cube! |website=Official Phillip Schofield.com |date=1 February 2012}}</ref> Along with other high-profile athletes, Farah later took part in the [[2012 Olympic hunger summit]] at [[10 Downing Street]] hosted by Prime Minister [[David Cameron]], part of a series of international efforts which have sought to respond to the return of hunger as a high-profile global issue.<ref name=\"Osutpghs\">{{cite news |last=Heaven |first=Douglas |title=Olympic stars unite to promote global hunger summit |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn22172-olympic-stars-unite-to-promote-global-hunger-summit.html |accessdate=16 August 2012 |newspaper=New Scientist |date=14 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nOlympic memorabilia featuring and signed by Farah has also been auctioned off to raise funds for the [[London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games]] (LOCOG).<ref name=\"Mfssalta\">{{cite news |title=Mo Farah stamp sold at London 2012 auction |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-22332061 |accessdate=1 August 2013 |newspaper=BBC |date=28 April 2013}}</ref> In 2013, he joined legislators and activists in a campaign urging [[Barclays Bank]] to repeal its decision to withdraw from the UK remittance market. Farah often used money transfer operators to send remittances to family, and some of the world's largest organisations and charities, including the UN and his own foundation, likewise paid staff and channelled funds through these services.<ref name=\"Mfpwbnterts\">{{cite news |last=Muir |first=Hugh |title=Mo Farah pleads with Barclays not to end remittances to Somalia |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/jul/26/mo-farah-barclays-remittance-market |accessdate=29 July 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=26 July 2013|location=London}}</ref> In March 2013, Farah, singer [[Robbie Williams]], and a number of other celebrities also urged Chancellor [[George Osborne]] to clamp down on global corporations that avoid paying taxes in poor countries in which they operate.<ref>https://londonlovesbusiness.com/mo-farah-and-robbie-williams-call-for-clampdown-on-tax-dodgers/</ref> He has also expressed support for research into brain tumours.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/stars-back-brain-tumour-funding-after-girl-6-given-two-years-to-live-a3380176.html |title=Stars back brain tumour funding after girl, 6, given two years to live |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=27 October 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 August 2017, Farah became a global ambassador for Marathon Kids. Speaking of his new role, Farah said, \"I love running, and it's given me and my family so much. As a dad, I know how important it is for my children to be active, and I'm honoured to have the chance to inspire kids to run with Marathon Kids.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.nike.com/news/mo-farah-marathon-kids |title=Mo Farah Reveals his Next Step|website=Nike News|access-date=10 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Endorsements, advertising and sponsorships===\nFarah has endorsement deals with a number of companies, including [[PACE Sports Management]], [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[Lucozade]], [[Quorn]], [[Bupa]] and [[Virgin Media]].<ref name=\"Usborne\"/> His work with Nike Inc. includes marketing of clothing and shoes.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.oregonlive.com/playbooks-profits/index.ssf/2014/01/nike_commercial_features_seatt.html |work=The Oregonian |title=Nike commercial features Seattle Seahawks cornerback Richard Sherman |date=20 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mofarahstore.bigcartel.com/product/run-mobot-tee |title=Men's 'Mobot' Tee |website=Mo Farah Store |accessdate=13 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424051033/http://mofarahstore.bigcartel.com/product/run-mobot-tee |archivedate=24 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Duffin\">{{cite news |last=Duffin |first=Claire |title=London 2012: Athletes in line to make millions after the Games |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/9468761/London-2012-Athletes-in-line-to-make-millions-after-the-Games.html |accessdate=16 August 2012 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=11 August 2012}}</ref> In order to preserve his earnings after taxes, Farah also applied in 2013 to have his main place of residence changed to Portland, where he spends most of the year training.<ref name=\"Ohmfatbteibtsm\"/>\n\nIn December 2013, Farah signed a marketing deal with [[Quorn (food product)|Quorn]], part of a multimillion-pound campaign aimed at doubling the firm's sales. He led television advertisements for Quorn's [[vegetarian]] forms of protein, with the campaign scheduled to last throughout the following year.<ref>{{cite web |first=Lisa |last=Riley |url=http://www.thegrocer.co.uk/fmcg/quorn-signs-up-mo-farah-for-new-ads-appealing-to-fitness-fans/352941.article |title=Quorn signs up Mo Farah for new ads appealing to fitness fans |website=The Grocer |date=21 December 2013 |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Travel security===\nIn 2012\u20132013, Farah intimated that he had been stopped a number of times by [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection|U.S. Customs]] officials under suspicion of being a [[Terrorism|terrorist]], which he attributed to confusion between his full name \"Mohamed\" and a computerised check-in process. On one occasion after the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympics]], he said that he had attempted to prove his identity by showing his [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] gold medals to customs officials, but that this was not accepted.<ref name=\"Ohmhiutb\">{{cite news |title=Olympic Hero Mo Held in US Terror Blunder |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1031513/olympic-hero-mo-held-in-us-terror-blunder |accessdate=1 January 2013 |newspaper=Sky News |date=30 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] signed an executive order temporarily suspending the immigration of Somali-born U.S. permanent residents, Farah made a statement on his Facebook account stating that \"I will have to tell my children that Daddy might not be able to come home.\"<ref>{{cite web |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/somalia-born-olympic-champion-mo-farah-troubled-trump-s-travel-n713786 |title=Somalia-born Olympic Champion Mo Farah Troubled by Trump's Travel Ban |website=NBC News |date= |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Farah posted a video on Instagram depicting what he alleges to be racial harassment at [[Munich Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/43308999|title=Mo Farah: Olympic champion says he was racially harassed at German airport|date=6 March 2018|publisher=|accessdate=22 April 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Fancy Bears and Salazar==\n===Fancy Bears leak===\nIn July 2017, the Russian hacking group [[Fancy Bears]] leaked a database from [[International Association of Athletics Federations]] which reportedly showed that Farah was once recorded \"atypical\" values on his Athlete Biological Passport in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mo Farah was investigated, then cleared, of doping by IAAF expert |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/jul/05/mo-farah-suspected-cleared-doping-iaaf-expert |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=7 November 2018 |date=6 July 2017}}</ref> The controversy came after it emerged that an IAAF expert had regarded Farah's blood values as suspicious, and had written next to his name: \u201cLikely doping; Passport suspicious: further data is required\u201d. However, Farah was cleared of wrongdoing by April 2016 after a separate leaked spreadsheet said his records had been \u201cnow flagged as normal with the last sample\u201d.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Fancy Bears leak says IAAF cleared Mo Farah after doping fear |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/athletics/2017/07/05/new-fancy-bears-leak-says-iaaf-cleared-mo-farah-doping-fear/|website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=7 November 2018 |date=5 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Salazar Ban===\nIn October 2019, Mo Farah's former coach Salazar and NOP doctor Dr Jeffrey Brown both received four year bans from athletics for the trafficking of testosterone, the prohibited use of L-carnitine, and tampering with doping controls.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url= https://www.usada.org/sanction/aaa-panel-4-year-sanctions-alberto-salazar-jeffrey-brown/ |title =AAA Panel Imposes 4-Year Sanctions on Alberto Salazar and Dr. Jeffrey Brown for Multiple Anti-Doping Rule Violations |accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n===Athletics===\n* 2006 British Athletics Writers' Association Award<ref name=\"sportsjournalists.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsjournalists.co.uk/site/bawa/ |title=Farah: male athlete of 2016 |website=British Athletics Writers' Association |date= |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n* 2010 British Athletics Writers' Association Award<ref name=\"sportsjournalists.co.uk\"/>\n* 2010 Best Senior Athlete of 2010 (UK Aviva Athletics Awards)<ref>{{cite news |title=Aviva Athletics Awards 2010 |url=http://www.uka.org.uk/media/news/news-archive-pre-2011/december-2010/06-12-10-aviva-athletics-awards/ |website=UKA.org.uk |date=6 December 2012 |accessdate=19 September 2012}}</ref>\n* 2010 London Youth Games Hall of Fame<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londonyouthgames.org/news.asp?section=26&itemid=1323&search= |title=London Youth Games Hall of Fame 2010 |website=London Youth Games.org |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=16 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921130501/http://www.londonyouthgames.org/news.asp?section=26&itemid=1323&search= |archive-date=21 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* 2011 British Athletics Writers' Association Award<ref name=\"Muwraw\"/>\n* 2011 European Athlete of the Year<ref name=\"Muwraw\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/15181590.stm |website=BBC News |title=Farah handed 2011 European award |date=5 October 2011}}</ref>\n* 2011 [[BBC Sports Personality of the Year Award]], 3rd place\n* 2011 [[Athletics Weekly]] International Male Athlete\n* 2012 British Athletics Writers' Association Award<ref>{{cite news |title=Farah and Ennis voted British Athletes of the Year |url=http://uka.org.uk/media/news/october-2012/26-10-12-farah-ennis/ |website=UKA.org.uk |date=26 October 2012 |accessdate=28 October 2012}}</ref>\n* 2012 European Athlete of the Year<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/9589319/Mo-Farah-voted-European-Male-Athlete-of-Year-for-second-year-in-a-row.html |title=Mo Farah voted European male athlete of the year for second year |first=Simon |last=Hart |date=5 October 2012 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref>\n* 2012 [[Laureus World Sports Award for Breakthrough of the Year]], nominee\n* 2012 Athletics Weekly International Male Athlete\n* 2013 IAAF World Athlete of the Year, finalist\n* 2013 British Athletics Writers' Association Award<ref name=\"sportsjournalists.co.uk\"/>\n* 2013 Athletics Weekly International Male Athlete<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.athleticsweekly.com/news/aw-readers-choice-award-winners/ |title=Farah, Adams and Rees among AW Readers' Choice award winners |website=Athletics Weekly |date=5 December 2013 |accessdate=13 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140216110604/http://www.athleticsweekly.com/news/aw-readers-choice-award-winners/ |archivedate=16 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 2013 Laureus World Sports Award for Sportsman of the Year, nominee\n* 2013 [[British Olympic Association]] Olympic athlete of the year<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teamgb.com/news/boa-announce-olympic-athletes-year-2013 |title=BOA Announce Olympic Athletes of the Year 2013 |website=Team GB |date=23 December 2013 |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n* 2013 AIPS Europe Sportsmen of the Year \u2013 ''Frank Taylor Trophy''\n* 2013 [[Rodale, Inc.]], [[Running Times]] \u2013 Runner of the Year<ref>{{cite web |last=Young |first=Ken |url=http://www.runnersworld.com/elite-runners/the-running-times-2013-runners-of-the-year?page=2 |title=The Running Times 2013 Runners of the Year |website=Running Times |date=30 December 2013 |accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n* 2014 [[Jesse Owens International Athlete Trophy]], nominee<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/usain-bolt-mo-farah-and-serena-williams-top-prize |title=Usain Bolt, Mo Farah and Serena Williams up for top prize |website=The Voice Online |date=31 January 2014 |accessdate=13 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140706125938/http://voice-online.co.uk/article/usain-bolt-mo-farah-and-serena-williams-top-prize |archive-date=6 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* 2014 Laureus World Sports Award for Sportsman of the Year, nominee\n* 2015 World Record, [[Two miles|2-mile]] run, [[Birmingham]]\n* Runners World top 50 influential individuals in running<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rw.runnersworld.com/the50/ |title=The 50 Most Influential People in Running |website=Runner's World |accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n* LetsRun.com number 1 in 2015 year-end world ranking for long-distance runners<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.letsrun.com/news/2015/12/2015-lrc-year-end-rankings-mens-5000-mo-farah-else-1-world-ben-true-galen-rupp-ryan-hill-lead-fine-crop-americans/ |title=2015 LRC Year-End Rankings, Men's 5,000: Mo Farah (Who Else?) Is No. 1 in World; Ben True, Galen Rupp & Ryan Hill Lead A Fine Crop of Americans |website=LetsRun.com |date= |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>\n* 2015 fastest men's 10,000-meter runner<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.letsrun.com/news/2015/12/2015-lrc-year-end-rankings-mens-10000-surprise-surprise-mo-farah-galen-rupp-world-us-1s/ |title=2015 LRC Year-End Rankings, Men's 10,000: Surprise, Surprise \u2013 Mo Farah And Galen Rupp Are The World And US #1s |website=LetsRun.com |date= |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>\n* 2016 BAWA Athlete of the Year<ref>{{cite web |last=Weekly |first=Athletics |url=http://www.athleticsweekly.com/featured/jessica-ennis-hill-mo-farah-bawa-athletes-of-the-year-53159 |title=Jessica Ennis-Hill and Mo Farah are BAWA athletes of the year |website=Athletics Weekly |date=4 November 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n* 2016 British Athletics Supporters Club athlete of the year<ref>{{cite web |last=Weekly |first=Athletics |url=http://www.athleticsweekly.com/featured/mo-farah-voted-basc-athlete-of-the-year-53743 |title=Mo Farah voted BASC athlete of the year |website=Athletics Weekly |date=20 November 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n* 2016 [[Athletics Weekly]] International Male Athlete of the Year, ahead of [[Usain Bolt]]<ref name=\"athleticsweekly.com\">{{cite web |last=Weekly |first=Athletics |url=http://www.athleticsweekly.com/featured/farah-ennis-hill-winners-2016-aw-readers-choice-awards-54331 |title=Farah and Ennis-Hill among winners in 2016 AW Readers' Choice Awards |website=Athletics Weekly |date=8 December 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n* 2016 Athletics Weekly British Male Athlete of the Year<ref name=\"athleticsweekly.com\"/>\n* 2017 Sportsman of the Year at the [[Lycamobile]] British Ethnic Diversity Sports Awards (BEDSAs)<ref name=\"voice-online\">{{cite news |last=Hinds|first=Rodney|url=http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/british-ethnic-diversity-sports-awards-honoured-sir-mo|title=British Ethnic Diversity Sports Awards honoured Sir Mo|work= |location= |publisher=Voice Online|date=23 March 2017|accessdate=1 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"sportingequals\">{{cite news|last=Trehan|first=Dev|url=http://www.sportingequals.org.uk/news-blogs/bedsa-2017-highlights.html|title=BEDSA 2017 Highlights|work=|location=|publisher=Sporting Equals|date=7 May 2017|accessdate=1 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180401213326/http://www.sportingequals.org.uk/news-blogs/bedsa-2017-highlights.html|archive-date=1 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/39314017|title=Mo Farah & Kadeena Cox win British Ethnic Diversity Sports Awards awards|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=18 March 2017}}</ref>\n*[[2017 BBC Sports Personality of the Year Award]], 1st place\n\n===Other===\n* 2013 Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (CBE)<ref name=Tnyh />\n* 2013 Premier Inn Celebrity Dad of The Year<ref name=\"Imfncdoty\">{{cite news |title=Mo Farah named Celebrity Dad of the Year |url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2013-06-15/mo-farah-named-celebrity-dad-of-the-year/ |accessdate=1 August 2013 |newspaper=ITV |date=15 