ds-54331 |title=Farah and Ennis-Hill among winners in 2016 AW Readers' Choice Awards |website=Athletics Weekly |date=8 December 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n* 2016 Athletics Weekly British Male Athlete of the Year<ref name=\"athleticsweekly.com\"/>\n* 2017 Sportsman of the Year at the [[Lycamobile]] British Ethnic Diversity Sports Awards (BEDSAs)<ref name=\"voice-online\">{{cite news |last=Hinds|first=Rodney|url=http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/british-ethnic-diversity-sports-awards-honoured-sir-mo|title=British Ethnic Diversity Sports Awards honoured Sir Mo|work= |location= |publisher=Voice Online|date=23 March 2017|accessdate=1 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"sportingequals\">{{cite news|last=Trehan|first=Dev|url=http://www.sportingequals.org.uk/news-blogs/bedsa-2017-highlights.html|title=BEDSA 2017 Highlights|work=|location=|publisher=Sporting Equals|date=7 May 2017|accessdate=1 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180401213326/http://www.sportingequals.org.uk/news-blogs/bedsa-2017-highlights.html|archive-date=1 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/39314017|title=Mo Farah & Kadeena Cox win British Ethnic Diversity Sports Awards awards|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=18 March 2017}}</ref>\n*[[2017 BBC Sports Personality of the Year Award]], 1st place\n\n===Other===\n* 2013 Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (CBE)<ref name=Tnyh />\n* 2013 Premier Inn Celebrity Dad of The Year<ref name=\"Imfncdoty\">{{cite news |title=Mo Farah named Celebrity Dad of the Year |url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2013-06-15/mo-farah-named-celebrity-dad-of-the-year/ |accessdate=1 August 2013 |newspaper=ITV |date=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n* 2013 Best at Sport award at the [[British Muslim Awards]]<ref name=\"asianimage\">{{cite magazine |last= |first= |url=http://www.asianimage.co.uk/news/10197507.Winners_honoured_at_British_Muslim_Awards/ |title=Winners honoured at British Muslim Awards |magazine=Asian Image |date=31 January 2013 |accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref>\n* 6th place, Freuds Heroes Index<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/wildlife-presenter-david-attenborough-is-named-the-uks-most-trustworthy-figure-9102139.html |location=London |newspaper=The Independent |first=Antonia |last=Molloy |title=Wildlife presenter David Attenborough is named the UK's most trustworthy figure |date=2 February 2014}}</ref>\n* 2014 World's 100 Most Powerful Arabs, ''[[Arabian Business]]''<ref name=\"Wompa\">{{cite web |title=World's 100 Most Powerful Arabs |url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/world-s-100-most-powerful-arabs-2014-543949.html?view=profile&itemid=544012#.U_OnJbt38jh |website=Arabian Business |accessdate=19 August 2014}}</ref>\n* 2015, clothing firm Rohan's 8th greatest [[Briton]] of all time<ref>{{cite web |last=Fox |first=Boudicca |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/50-greatest-britons-revealed-wills-6495706 |title=The 50 greatest Britons revealed: Wills and Kate are in but where are Bobby Moore and Thomas Hardy? \u2013 Mirror Online |website=Mirror.co.uk |date= |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>\n* 2015 [[London Evening Standard|Evening Standard]]'s top 25 most influential [[Demography of London|London]]ers<ref>Ashton, James (16 September 2015) [https://www.standard.co.uk/news/the1000/power-and-the-glory-george-osborne-and-england-rugby-captain-chris-robshaw-named-as-most-influential-a2948656.html The Progress 1000: George Osborne and England rugby captain Chris Robshaw named as most influential Londoners]. standard.co.uk</ref>\n* 2016 [[Sports Relief]] highest polled sporting [[London]] hero with 27% of the vote<ref>{{cite news |first=Lizzie |last=Edmonds |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/mo-farah-named-sports-hero-londoners-are-most-proud-of-a3167901.html |title=Mo Farah named sports hero Londoners are most proud of |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=29 January 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>\n* 2016, Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Award for Inspirational Athlete.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n* 2016, 5th most powerful [[Black British|Black Briton]], on 10th anniversary of Powerlist, African and Caribbean heritage listing<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/sir-lenny-henry-and-mo-farah-among-top-10-most-influential-black-britons-35159049.html |title=Sir Lenny Henry and Mo Farah among top 10 most influential black Britons |newspaper=Belfast Telegraph |date= |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n* 2017, Created a [[Knight Bachelor]] for services to Athletics.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61803 |date=31 December 2016 |supp=y |page=N2 }}</ref>\n* Awarded OLY post nominal title from World Olympians Association<ref>https://olympians.org/news/1127/oly-honours-for-olympic-legends/</ref>\n\n==National titles==\n* [[British Athletics Championships]]\n** 5000 metres: 2007, 2011\n* [[British Indoor Athletics Championships]]\n** 3000 metres: 2007\n* [[British 10K Championships]]\n** 10K run: 2011, 2012\n* [[British Marathon Championships]]\n** Marathon: 2014\n\n==Race results==\nAll information from [[Association of Road Racing Statisticians]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://more.arrs.run/runner/13567 |title=Mohamed Farah Mukhtar |website=[[Association of Road Racing Statisticians]] |accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===International competitions===\n{| {{AchievementTable|Event=yes}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1999\n|[[1999 World Youth Championships in Athletics|World Youth Championships]]\n|[[Bydgoszcz]], Poland\n|6th\n|3000 m\n|8:21.25\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[1999 European Cross Country Championships|European Cross Country Championships]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Velenje]], Slovenia\n|5th\n|Junior individual\n|23:18\n|-\n|bgcolor=gold|1st\n|Junior team\n|26 pts\n|-\n|rowspan=5|2000\n|rowspan=2|[[2000 IAAF World Cross Country Championships|World Cross Country Championships]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Vilamoura]], Portugal\n|25th\n|[[2000 IAAF World Cross Country Championships \u201