[Guadalajara]]\n| align=\"left\" |{{flagg|pspew|al=c|pref=List of cities in|Mexico}}\n| align=\"center\" |[[File:Guadalajara 16 feb 2013 (cropped).jpg|125px]]\n|{{nts|5023000}}\n| align=\"left\" |[[Municipalities of Mexico|Municipality]]\n|{{nts|1460148}}\n|{{nts|151}}\n|{{nts|5002466}}\n|{{nts|2734}}\n|{{nts|}}\n|{{nts|}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of largest cities throughout history]]\n* [[List of towns and cities with 100,000 or more inhabitants]]\n* [[Number of urban areas by country]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://data.un.org/Data.aspx?d=POP&f=tableCode%3A240 UNSD Demographics Statistics \u2013 City population by sex, city and city type] \n* [https://nordpil.com/resources/world-database-of-large-cities/ Nordpil World Database of Large Urban Areas, 1950\u20132050]\n\n{{World's largest cities}}\n{{Cities}}\n{{portal bar|Geography|Lists}}\n\n[[Category:Cities-related lists of superlatives]]\n[[Category:Lists of cities (worldwide) by population]]\n[[Category:Urban geography]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{World city population tables}}\n\nThe [[United Nations]] uses three definitions for what constitutes a city, as not all cities in all jurisdictions are classified using the same criteria.<ref name=\"UNICEF\"/> Cities may be defined as the cities proper, the extent of their urban area, or their metropolitan regions.<ref name=\"UNICEF\"/> The largest city by population using the city proper definition, which is the area under the administrative boundaries of a local government, is [[Chongqing]], [[China]]. The largest city by population using the metropolitan area definition, which is a loose term referring to urban area and its primary commuter areas, is [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]. The largest city by population using the urban area definition, which is a loose term referring to a contiguous area with a certain population density, is also Tokyo, Japan.\n\n==Common city definitions==\n=== City proper (administrative) ===\n{{Main|City proper}}\n{{maplink|frame=yes|type=shape|stroke-width=2|id=Q11725|title=Chongqing|stroke-color=#000000|zoom=6|frame-lat=29.558|frame-long=107.50|frame-width=300|frame-height=240|frame-coordinates={{coord|30|00|30|N|107|34|00|E|region:CN-50|display=it}}|type2=shape|stroke-width2=2|id2=Q40|title2=Austria|text=The municipality of [[Chongqing]], whose administrative area is around the size of [[Austria]], has the largest population for a [[city proper]]. However, more than 70% of its residents actually live in [[rural area]]s.}}\nA city can be defined by its administrative boundaries ([[city proper]]). UNICEF<ref name=\"UNICEF\"/> defines city proper as \"the population living within the administrative boundaries of a city or controlled directly from the city by a single authority.\" A city proper is a locality defined according to legal or political boundaries and an administratively recognised urban status that is usually characterised by some form of [[local government]].<ref name=\"wup2007\">{{cite web|url=http://esa.un.org/unup/index.asp?panel=6 |title=World Urbanization Prospects: The 2007 Revision Population Database |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=26 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100822053414/http://esa.un.org/unup/index.asp?panel=6 |archivedate=22 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://millenniumindicators.un.org/unsd/demographic/sconcerns/densurb/densurbanNotes.htm |title=United Nations Statistics Division \u2013 Demographic and Social Statistics |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=26 July 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623192351/http://millenniumindicators.un.org/unsd/demographic/sconcerns/densurb/densurbanNotes.htm |archivedate=23 June 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Demographic Yearbook 2005, Volume 57 |year=2008 |publisher=United Nations |isbn=978-92-1-051099-8 |page=241 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=OwfGJtkpCbwC&pg=PA241 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502022103/https://books.google.com/books?id=OwfGJtkpCbwC&pg=PA241 |archivedate=2 May 2016  }}</ref> Cities proper and their boundaries and population data may not include suburbs.<ref name=\"wup2003\">{{cite book |title=World Urbanization Prospects: The 2003 Revision |year=2004 |publisher=United Nations |isbn=92-1-151396-0 <!-- This is the correct ISBN. The number on the copyright page of the book is invalid. --> |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oxOAckK2stYC}}</ref>\n\nThe use of city proper as defined by administrative boundaries may not include suburban areas where an important proportion of the population working or studying in the city lives.<ref name=\"wup2003\" /> Because of this definition, the city proper population figure may differ greatly with the urban area population figure, as many cities are amalgamations of smaller municipalities (Australia), and conversely, many Chinese cities govern territories that extend well beyond the traditional \"city proper\" into suburban and rural areas.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alexander|first1=Ruth|title=The world's biggest cities: How do you measure them? |url = https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-16761784|date=29 January 2012|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302023557/http://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-16761784|archivedate=2 March 2015  }}</ref> The Chinese municipality of [[Chongqing]], which claims the largest city proper in the world, comprises a huge administrative area of 82,403 km<sup>2</sup>, around the size of [[Austria]]. However, more than 70% of its 30-million population are actually agricultural workers living in a [[rural area|rural setting]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-16761784|title=Which is the world's biggest city?|first=Ruth|last=Alexander|date=29 January 2012|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.id/books?id=vuQRDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA83&lpg=PA83#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=China Dreams: 20 Visions of the Future|first=William A.|last=Callahan|date=12 April 2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n=== Metropolitan area ===\n{{Main|Metropolitan area}}\n\nA city can be defined by the inhabitants of its [[demography|demographic]] population, as by [[metropolitan area]], [[labour market]] area, or similar in a metropolitan area. UNICEF<ref name=\"UNICEF\"/> defines metropolitan area as follows:\n\n{{quote|A formal local government area comprising the urban area as a whole and its primary commuter areas, typically formed around a city with a large concentration of people (i.e., a population of at least 100,000). In addition to the city proper, a metropolitan area includes both the surrounding territory with urban levels of residential density and some additional lower-density areas that are adjacent to and linked to the city (e.g., through frequent transport, road linkages or commuting facilities).}}\n\nIn many countries, metropolitan areas are established either with an official organisation or only for statistical purposes. In the United States, [[metropolitan statistical area]] (MSA) is defined by the [[U.S. Office of Management and Budget]] (OMB) for statistical purpose.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/sites/default/files/omb/assets/omb/bulletins/fy2009/09-01.pdf |last=Nussle |first=Jim |title=Update of Statistical Area Definitions and Guidance on Their Uses |publisher=Office of Management and Budget |date=Nov 20, 2008 |pages=1\u20132 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104180847/http://www.whitehouse.gov/sites/default/files/omb/assets/omb/bulletins/fy2009/09-01.pdf |archivedate=2010-11-04 }}</ref> In the Philippines, metropolitan areas have an official agency, such as [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] (MMDA) which manages [[Metro Manila|Manila metropolitan area]].<ref>http://www.mmda.gov.ph/mmda-about-us.html</ref> Similar agencies exist in Indonesia such as Jabodetabekjur Development Cooperation Agency for [[Jakarta metropolitan area]].<ref>https://metro.tempo.co/read/1152868/3-masalah-utama-bksp-jabodetabekjur-yang-dipimpin-anies-baswedan?TerkiniUtama&campaign=TerkiniUtama_Click_10</ref>\n\n=== Urban area ===\n{{Main|Urban area}}\n{{See also|Number of urban areas by country}}\n[[File:Night in the Greater Tokyo Area ISS054.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Greater Tokyo Area|Tokyo]] is considered the world's largest city, with its urbanisation exceeding its [[city limits]].]]\nA city can be defined as a conditionally [[Geographic contiguity|contiguous]] [[urban area]], without regard to territorial or other boundaries inside an urban area. [[UNICEF]]<ref name=\"UNICEF\">{{cite web |url = http://www.unicef.org/sowc2012/statistics.php |title=SOWC-2012-DEFINITIONS|publisher=[[UNICEF]]|accessdate=29 January 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208114052/http://www.unicef.org/sowc2012/statistics.php |archivedate=8 December 2013}}</ref> defines urban area as follows:\n\n{{quote|The definition of \"urban\" varies from country to country, and, with periodic reclassification, can also vary within one country over time, making direct comparisons difficult. An urban area can be defined by one or more of the following: administrative criteria or political boundaries (e.g., area within the jurisdiction of a municipality or town committee), a threshold population size (where the minimum for an urban settlement is typically in the region of 2,000 people, although this varies globally between 200 and 50,000), population density, economic function (e.g., where a significant majority of the population is not primarily engaged in agriculture, or where there is surplus employment) or the presence of urban characteristics (e.g., paved streets, electric lighting, sewerage).}}\n\nAccording to [[Demographia]], an urban area is a continuously built up land mass of urban development that is within a labor market (metropolitan area or metropolitan region) and contains no [[rural area|rural land]].<ref name=\"Demographia\"/>\n\n== Largest cities ==\nThere are 81 cities with an urban population over 5,000,000 people according to the United Nations 2018 population estimates.\n<ref name=UNurbanarea>https://population.un.org/wup/Publications/Files/WUP2018-Highlights.pdf</ref>\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable mw-datatable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | City{{efn|For urban/metropolitan areas that have more than one [[core city]], the figure for their city proper should use either the most populous one (e.g. [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] for [[Rhine-Ruhr]], or [[Dallas]] for [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]) or the most well-known one (e.g. [[Manila]] for [[Metro Manila]], instead of [[Quezon City]]).}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Country\n! class=\"unsortable\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Skyline]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Urban agglomeration</br>(UN 2018</br>population estimates)<ref name=UNurbanarea/>\n! colspan=\"3\" | [[City proper]]{{efn|Figures taken from official census when  possible}}\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Metropolitan area]]{{efn|Figures taken from official census when possible}}\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Urban area]]</br>(Demographia)<ref name=\"Demographia\">{{cite web|title=Demographia World Urban Areas, 15th Annual Edition|url=http://www.demographia.com/db-worldua.pdf|publisher=[[Demographia]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207210003/http://www.demographia.com/db-worldua.pdf|archivedate=7 February 2020|date=April 2019|access-date=13 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! Definition\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Population\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Area<br>(km<sup>2</sup>)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Population\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Area<br>(km<sup>2</sup>)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Population\n! data-sort-type=\"numb