{"title_page": "AIRES Flight 8250", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| image = AIRES-737-700.JPG\n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = HK-4682, the aircraft involved, seen at [[Bogot\u00e1 Airport]] five months before the crash\n| occurrence_type = Accident\n| date = {{Start date|2010|08|16|df=y}}\n| summary = [[Controlled flight into terrain | Runway undershoot]] due to [[pilot error]], aggravated by the [[Sensory_illusions_in_aviation#Black-hole_approach|black hole approach illusion]].<ref>''[[Mayday]]''. Season 20 Episode 5, \"Runway Breakup\".</ref>\n| site = [[Gustavo Rojas Pinilla International Airport]], [[San Andr\u00e9s, San Andr\u00e9s y Providencia|San Andr\u00e9s]], Colombia\n| coordinates = {{coord|12|34|45|N|81|43|10|W|source:kolossus-ptwiki_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| aircraft_type = [[Boeing 737-700|Boeing 737-73V]]\n| aircraft_name = \n| operator = [[AIRES]]\n| IATA = \n| ICAO = ARE8250\n| callsign = \n| tail_number = HK-4682\n| origin = [[El Dorado International Airport]], [[Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia\n| destination = [[Gustavo Rojas Pinilla International Airport]], [[San Andr\u00e9s (island)|San Andr\u00e9s]], Colombia\n| occupants = 131\n| passengers = 125\n| crew = 6\n| fatalities= 2\n| injuries = 129\n| survivors = 129\n}}\n\n'''AIRES Flight 8250''' was a domestic scheduled passenger flight that on 16 August 2010 crashed on landing at night in poor weather on the Colombian island of [[San Andr\u00e9s (island)|San Andr\u00e9s]], killing 2 of the 131 people on board. The aircraft, an [[AIRES]]-operated [[Boeing 737-700]], was arriving from the Colombian capital [[Bogot\u00e1]] when it heavily touched down short of the runway, breaking up in three sections.\n\nThe official investigation concluded that the crash was caused by the misjudgement by the crew of the aircraft's altitude during the last phase of the approach.<ref name=\"Final report\">{{cite report |title=Accidente ocurrido el d\u00eda 16 de Agosto de 2010 a  la aeronave Boeing 737-700, Matr\u00edcula HK-4682 en el Aeropuerto Internacional Gustavo Rojas Pinilla de la Isla de San Andr\u00e9s - Colombia |url=http://reports.aviation-safety.net/2010/20100816-0_B737_HK-4682.pdf |accessdate=22 September 2019 |publisher=[[UAEAC]]}}</ref>\n\n== History of the flight ==\nFlight 8250 was operated by the local, privately owned Colombian airline [[AIRES]].<ref name=Reuters16Aug2010CrashesDuringStorm/><ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/> The aircraft was on a flight from Bogot\u00e1 to the Colombian island of [[San Andr\u00e9s (island)|San Andr\u00e9s]], in the [[Caribbean]].<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/> A popular tourist destination, San Andres Island is about {{convert|190|km|mi nmi|abbr=}} east of the Nicaraguan coast.<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/>\n\nThe flight took off from Bogot\u00e1's [[El Dorado International Airport]] at 00:07 en route to [[Gustavo Rojas Pinilla International Airport]] with 125 passengers and six crew. [[pilot in command|Captain]] Wilson Gutierrez was the pilot flying (PF) while [[first officer (aeronautics)|First Officer]] Camilo Pineyros Rodriguez was pilot monitoring (PM).<ref name=RCN16Aug2010/>\n\n=== Accident ===\nThe crash occurred as the aircraft landed at San Andr\u00e9s at 1:49&nbsp;am local Western Caribbean Time ([[UTC\u221205:00]]).<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/><ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> The Boeing 737 broke up into three main sections.<ref name=AviationHerald/> The impact occurred about {{convert|260|ft|m|-1}} before the start of the runway, with wreckage spread about another {{convert|328|ft|m}}.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> The aircraft skidded along the runway, fracturing the landing gear and ripping one engine from the wings.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/> The aircraft's nose and first eight rows of seating came to rest on the runway pointing in a different direction to the rest of the wreckage.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> Airport fire crews quickly doused a small fire that had started on a wing.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/> As a result of the accident, the Comit\u00e9 Regional de Prevenci\u00f3n y Atenci\u00f3n de Desastres was mobilized.<ref name=Eltiempo/>\n\n== Aircraft ==\nThe aircraft involved was a [[Boeing 737-700|Boeing 737-73V]],<ref group=Notes>The aircraft was a Boeing 737-700 model; Boeing assigns a unique code for each company that buys one of its aircraft, which is applied as an [[infix]] to the model number at the time the aircraft is built, hence \"737-73V\".</ref> registration HK-4682, with serial number (MSN) 32416, construction number 1270.<ref name=Airfleets/> The aircraft was built in 2003,<ref name=Airfleets/> and was first delivered to [[EasyJet]] registered as G-EZJU. It was then sold to AIRES in March 2010.<ref name=Airfleets/> Investigators said the day after the crash that the aircraft's maintenance log was up to date.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/>\n\n== Passengers and crew ==\n[[File:Seatmap of Aires 8250 (en).svg|thumbnail|right|Seat plan]]\nThere were contradictory reports as to how many people were aboard the aircraft.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> Reports range from 121 passengers and 6 crew members,<ref name=Reuters16Aug2010CrashesDuringStorm/> 131 passengers and crew,<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/> and at least 127 people aboard.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> The report of 131 people was further broken down as 121 adult passengers and four minors.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> Reports the day after the accident, settled on 131 people aboard: 125 passengers and 6 crew.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/><ref name=ABCNews17Aug2010InsideMiracle/><ref name=BBCNews17Aug2010AirCrashMiracle/><ref name=Yahoo17Aug2010WomanDies/>\n\nOne early report stated that 114 people were injured in the crash, and that of 99 passengers taken to the Amor de Patria Hospital on San Andr\u00e9s, only 4 had suffered major injuries.<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/> Reports a day later settled on a figure of 119 people being taken to local hospitals, mostly with minor injuries.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/><ref name=Yahoo17Aug2010WomanDies/> Thirteen survivors, including four with serious injuries, were flown to Bogota for treatment.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/>\n\nInitial reports indicated one fatality, an elderly lady dying of a heart attack.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/17/world/americas/17colombia.html</ref> The final fatality count was two. Autopsy revealed that a 68-year-old woman suffered a ruptured aorta and ruptured liver.<ref name=AviationHerald /> She died on the way to the hospital.<ref name=Reuters16Aug2010CrashesDuringStorm/><ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/> The second fatality was a girl;<ref>\"[http://www.aires.aero/comunicado_06.html Comunicado de Prensa 06] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100909003235/http://www.aires.aero/comunicado_06.html |date=9 September 2010 }}.\" AIRES. Retrieved on 15 September 2010.</ref> she sustained substantial brain damage{{citation needed|date=September 2010}} and died 16 days after the accident.<ref>https://www.elpais.com.co/colombia/companeras-de-colegio-dieron-el-ultimo-adios-a-maria-camila-angarita.html</ref>\n\nOne report stated that the passenger list included six Americans, five Mexicans, four Brazilians, four Ecuadorians and two Germans, the rest being Colombians.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> Another report stated there were three Americans aboard.<ref name=Caracol/> A later report put the number of non-Colombians aboard as 'at least 16'.<ref name=BBCNews17Aug2010AirCrashMiracle/>\n\n== Investigation ==\nColombia's civil aviation authority, [[Special Administrative Unit of Civil Aeronautics]], and the [[Colombian Air Force]] opened an investigation into the accident.<ref name=Eltiempo/> The airport was closed as investigators examined the wreckage.<ref name=Reuters16Aug2010CrashesDuringStorm/> The closure was expected to last until 06:00 on 17 August.<ref name=Eltiempo/>\n\nThe aircraft reportedly crashed in bad weather, while a storm was reported in the area, but not at the airport.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> The [[METAR]] (aviation routine weather observation message) report in force at the time of the accident indicated that the wind was from the east north east at {{convert|6|kn|km/h mph|abbr=}}, visibility was good and that the runway was wet.<ref group=Notes>Raw data from the [[METAR]] report were: SKSP 160500Z 07006KT 9999 FEW016 SCT200 29/26 A2990=Translated: Gustavo Rojas Pinilla International Airport date: 16th day of the month, time: 0500 zulu/UTC, wind: 070\u00b0 at 6 kt, visibility: 10&nbsp;km or more, few clouds at 1600&nbsp;ft., scattered clouds at 20000&nbsp;ft., temperature 29&nbsp;\u00b0C, dew point 26&nbsp;\u00b0C, altimeter setting (pressure) 29.90 inHg.</ref><ref name=AviationHerald /> The aircraft \"landed in the middle of an intense electrical storm\" according to Colonel Barrero.<ref name=Reuters16Aug2010CrashesDuringStorm/>\n\nPassenger accounts the day after the crash detailed how the approach appeared to have been going normally, with the flight attendants having made the passengers ready for landing, when the crash occurred suddenly and without warning.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/><ref name=ABCNews17Aug2010InsideMiracle/><ref name=BBCNews17Aug2010AirCrashMiracle/> The pilot did not report an emergency to the tower.<ref name=Yahoo17Aug2010WomanDies/> There were conflicting reports over what caused the crash, suggesting that the landing was disrupted after the aircraft was hit by a [[downdraft]], or struck by [[lightning]].<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> The pilot said that the aircraft was struck by lightning. Officials refused to comment on the reports of a lightning strike,<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/><ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/><ref name=Eltiempo/> although subsequent research proved that{{specify|date=December 2018}} was not true. No aircraft has had an accident caused by lightning [[LANSA Flight 508|since 1971]]. The airport was not fitted with equipment such as a Doppler radar, used to detect wind shear.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/>\n\nBoth the [[flight recorder|flight data and cockpit voice recorders]] were recovered from the wreckage.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/> Based on the pattern of wreckage, investigators concluded that the aircraft had broken up on impact and not while in the air.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/>\n\nThe U.S. [[National Transportation Safety Board]] sent a team to support the Colombian-led investigation as representatives of the manufacturer's state.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.ntsb.gov/Pressrel/2010/100816c.html |title=NTSB sending team to assist government of Colombia with today's 737 accident |date=16 August 2010 |publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]] }}</ref>\n\nAlmost one year after the accident, on 15 July 2011, the Security Council of Aeron\u00e1utica Civil concluded that the cause of the accident was the execution of the final approach below the glide path, due to an error of judgment by the crew who believed they were much higher. This is typical of a \"black hole\" illusion, which is experienced during a night approach to a low contrast runway environment surrounded by bright lights, aggravated by heavy rain.<ref name=\"Final report\"/> Aerona\u00fatica Civil recommended retraining of the crew. Although the accident was caused by human error, Aerona\u00fatica representative Colonel Carlos Silva reminded that the purpose of the investigation was not to apportion blame but to prevent aircraft accidents that may occur in the future.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/colombia/otraszonas/ARTICULO-WEB-NEW_NOTA_INTERIOR-9916084.html|title=Error del piloto y mal tiempo, causas del accidente de avi\u00f3n de Aires|date=15 July 2011|work=[[El Tiempo (Colombia)|El Tiempo]]|accessdate=19 January 2013|language=Spanish|trans-title=Pilot error and bad weather, causes of the plane crash in Aires}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Notes}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=AviationHerald>{{cite web |url=http://www.avherald.com/h?article=42fb63a9&opt=0 | title=Accident: Aires B737 at San Andres Island on 16 Aug 2010, landed short of runway and broke up |accessdate=19 August 2010 |date=16 August 2010 |work=Aviation Herald}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Airfleets>{{cite web|url=http://www.airfleets.net/ficheapp/plane-b737ng-32416.htm |title=Boeing 737 Next Gen \u2013 MSN 32416  |publisher=Airfleets |accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Reuters16Aug2010CrashesDuringStorm>{{cite news\n|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idAFTRE67F2AI20100816\n|title=Colombian airliner crashes during storm leaving one dead\n|publisher=Reuters\n|date=16 August 2010\n|accessdate=16 August 2010\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100818183912/https://af.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idAFTRE67F2AI20100816| archivedate= 18 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Eltiempo>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.eltiempo.com/colombia/caribe/accidente-de-avion-en-san-andres_7866340-1\n |title       = Ministro de Transporte descart\u00f3 fallas t\u00e9cnicas de la aeronave que se accident\u00f3 en San Andr\u00e9s\n |publisher   = El Tiempo\n |language    = Spanish\n |accessdate  = 16 August 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120928084901/http://www.eltiempo.com/colombia/caribe/accidente-de-avion-en-san-andres_7866340-1\n |archivedate = 28 September 2012\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Caracol>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.caracol.com.co/nota.aspx?id=1341509\n|title=Ministro de Transporte atribuy\u00f3 al clima el accidente a\u00e9reo en San Andr\u00e9s |publisher=Caracol\n|language=Spanish\n|accessdate=16 August 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart>{{cite news\n|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/americas/08/16/colombia.plane.fatality/index.html\n|title=Jet breaks apart during landing in Colombia\n|publisher=CNN\n|date=16 August 2010\n|accessdate=16 August 2010\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100818164414/http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/americas/08/16/colombia.plane.fatality/index.html| archivedate= 18 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-10988966\n|title=Colombia plane breaks into pieces after crash\n|publisher=BBC News\n|date=16 August 2010\n|accessdate=16 August 2010\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100816190031/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-10988966| archivedate= 16 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=RCN16Aug2010>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.rcnradio.com/noticias/nacional/16-08-10/gobierno-no-descarta-que-un-rayo-causar-el-accidente-reo\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715161216/http://www.rcnradio.com/noticias/nacional/16-08-10/gobierno-no-descarta-que-un-rayo-causar-el-accidente-reo\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=15 July 2011\n |title=Gobierno no descarta que un rayo causar\u00e1 el accidente a\u00e9reo \n |publisher=RCN Radio \n |language=Spanish \n |date=16 August 2010 \n |accessdate=16 August 2010 \n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Yahoo17Aug2010WomanDies>{{cite news\n |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20100816/ap_on_re_la_am_ca/lt_colombia_plane_crash \n |title='Miracle' in Colombia crash: Woman dies, 130 live \n |publisher=Yahoo \n |date=17 August 2010 \n |accessdate=17 August 2010 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816171706/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20100816/ap_on_re_la_am_ca/lt_colombia_plane_crash \n |archivedate=16 August 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n  \n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gw3-tyohDhSGDplj8TPrYOq3ojSwD9HLAFFG0\n|title=130 survive 'miracle' plane crash in Colombia\n|agency=Associated Press\n|date=17 August 2010\n|accessdate=17 August 2010\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100820080305/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gw3-tyohDhSGDplj8TPrYOq3ojSwD9HLAFFG0| archivedate= 20 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ABCNews17Aug2010InsideMiracle>{{cite news\n|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/colombian-miracle-plane-crash-inside-story-passengers-survival/story?id=11416690&page=2\n|title=Colombian 'Miracle' Plane Crash: Inside the Story of Survival\n|publisher=ABC News\n|date=17 August 2010\n|accessdate=17 August 2010\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100821091502/http://abcnews.go.com/International/colombian-miracle-plane-crash-inside-story-passengers-survival/story?id=11416690&page=2| archivedate= 21 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=BBCNews17Aug2010AirCrashMiracle>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-10998821\n|title=Air crash 'miracle' for Colombia as plane breaks up\n|publisher=BBC News\n|date=17 August 2010\n|accessdate=17 August 2010\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100817194244/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-10998821| archivedate= 17 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{ASN accident|20100816-0}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110722140135/http://www.aires.aero/comunicado.html Para informaci\u00f3n del vuelo 8250] \u2013 AIRES {{in lang|es}} (Archive)\n* [[Special Administrative Unit of Civil Aeronautics]] [http://www.aerocivil.gov.co/AAeronautica/InvAccidentes/LAccidentes/Accidentes/FINAL%20HK4682%20-%20part%20I.pdf Final report] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6S5Vv36Xv?url=http://www.aerocivil.gov.co/AAeronautica/InvAccidentes/LAccidentes/Accidentes/FINAL%20HK4682%20-%20part%20I.pdf Archive])\n* [http://www.radiosantafe.com/2010/08/16/lista-oficial-de-ocupantes-del-avion-8250-de-aires/ Passenger list] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in Colombia}}\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 2010}}\n{{Portal bar|Aviation|Colombia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aires Flight 8250}}\n[[Category:2010 in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Boeing 737 Next Generation]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 2010]]\n[[Category:Archipelago of San Andr\u00e9s, Providencia and Santa Catalina]]\n[[Category:August 2010 events in South America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| image = AIRES-737-700.JPG\n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = HK-4682, the aircraft involved, seen at [[Bogot\u00e1 Airport]] five months before the crash\n| occurrence_type = Accident\n| date = {{Start date|2010|08|16|df=y}}\n| summary = [[Controlled flight into terrain]]\n| site = [[Gustavo Rojas Pinilla International Airport]], [[San Andr\u00e9s, San Andr\u00e9s y Providencia|San Andr\u00e9s]], Colombia\n| coordinates = {{coord|12|34|45|N|81|43|10|W|source:kolossus-ptwiki_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| aircraft_type = [[Boeing 737-700|Boeing 737-73V]]\n| aircraft_name = \n| operator = [[AIRES]]\n| IATA = \n| ICAO = ARE8250\n| callsign = \n| tail_number = HK-4682\n| origin = [[El Dorado International Airport]], [[Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia\n| destination = [[Gustavo Rojas Pinilla International Airport]], [[San Andr\u00e9s (island)|San Andr\u00e9s]], Colombia\n| occupants = 131\n| passengers = 125\n| crew = 6\n| fatalities= 2\n| injuries = 129\n| survivors = 129\n}}\n\n'''AIRES Flight 8250''' was a domestic scheduled passenger flight that on 16 August 2010 crashed on landing at night in poor weather on the Colombian island of [[San Andr\u00e9s (island)|San Andr\u00e9s]], killing 2 of the 131 people on board. The aircraft, an [[AIRES]]-operated [[Boeing 737-700]], was arriving from the Colombian capital [[Bogot\u00e1]] when it heavily touched down short of the runway, breaking up in three sections.\n\nThe official investigation concluded that the crash was caused by the misjudgement by the crew of the aircraft's altitude during the last phase of the approach.<ref name=\"Final report\">{{cite report |title=Accidente ocurrido el d\u00eda 16 de Agosto de 2010 a  la aeronave Boeing 737-700, Matr\u00edcula HK-4682 en el Aeropuerto Internacional Gustavo Rojas Pinilla de la Isla de San Andr\u00e9s - Colombia |url=http://reports.aviation-safety.net/2010/20100816-0_B737_HK-4682.pdf |accessdate=22 September 2019 |publisher=[[UAEAC]]}}</ref>\n\n== History of the flight ==\nFlight 8250 was operated by the local, privately owned Colombian airline [[AIRES]].<ref name=Reuters16Aug2010CrashesDuringStorm/><ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/> The aircraft was on a flight from Bogot\u00e1 to the Colombian island of [[San Andr\u00e9s (island)|San Andr\u00e9s]], in the [[Caribbean]].<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/> A popular tourist destination, San Andres Island is about {{convert|190|km|mi nmi|abbr=}} east of the Nicaraguan coast.<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/>\n\nThe flight took off from Bogot\u00e1's [[El Dorado International Airport]] at 00:07 en route to [[Gustavo Rojas Pinilla International Airport]] with 125 passengers and six crew. [[pilot in command|Captain]] Wilson Gutierrez was the pilot flying (PF) while [[first officer (aeronautics)|First Officer]] Camilo Pineyros Rodriguez was pilot monitoring (PM).<ref name=RCN16Aug2010/>\n\n=== Accident ===\nThe crash occurred as the aircraft landed at San Andr\u00e9s at 1:49&nbsp;am local Western Caribbean Time ([[UTC\u221205:00]]).<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/><ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> The Boeing 737 broke up into three main sections.<ref name=AviationHerald/> The impact occurred about {{convert|260|ft|m|-1}} before the start of the runway, with wreckage spread about another {{convert|328|ft|m}}.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> The aircraft skidded along the runway, fracturing the landing gear and ripping one engine from the wings.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/> The aircraft's nose and first eight rows of seating came to rest on the runway pointing in a different direction to the rest of the wreckage.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> Airport fire crews quickly doused a small fire that had started on a wing.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/> As a result of the accident, the Comit\u00e9 Regional de Prevenci\u00f3n y Atenci\u00f3n de Desastres was mobilized.<ref name=Eltiempo/>\n\n== Aircraft ==\nThe aircraft involved was a [[Boeing 737-700|Boeing 737-73V]],<ref group=Notes>The aircraft was a Boeing 737-700 model; Boeing assigns a unique code for each company that buys one of its aircraft, which is applied as an [[infix]] to the model number at the time the aircraft is built, hence \"737-73V\".</ref> registration HK-4682, with serial number (MSN) 32416, construction number 1270.<ref name=Airfleets/> The aircraft was built in 2003,<ref name=Airfleets/> and was first delivered to [[EasyJet]] registered as G-EZJU. It was then sold to AIRES in March 2010.<ref name=Airfleets/> Investigators said the day after the crash that the aircraft's maintenance log was up to date.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/>\n\n== Passengers and crew ==\n[[File:Seatmap of Aires 8250 (en).svg|thumbnail|right|Seat plan]]\nThere were contradictory reports as to how many people were aboard the aircraft.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> Reports range from 121 passengers and 6 crew members,<ref name=Reuters16Aug2010CrashesDuringStorm/> 131 passengers and crew,<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/> and at least 127 people aboard.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> The report of 131 people was further broken down as 121 adult passengers and four minors.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> Reports the day after the accident, settled on 131 people aboard: 125 passengers and 6 crew.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/><ref name=ABCNews17Aug2010InsideMiracle/><ref name=BBCNews17Aug2010AirCrashMiracle/><ref name=Yahoo17Aug2010WomanDies/>\n\nOne early report stated that 114 people were injured in the crash, and that of 99 passengers taken to the Amor de Patria Hospital on San Andr\u00e9s, only 4 had suffered major injuries.<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/> Reports a day later settled on a figure of 119 people being taken to local hospitals, mostly with minor injuries.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/><ref name=Yahoo17Aug2010WomanDies/> Thirteen survivors, including four with serious injuries, were flown to Bogota for treatment.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/>\n\nInitial reports indicated one fatality, an elderly lady dying of a heart attack.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/17/world/americas/17colombia.html</ref> The final fatality count was two. Autopsy revealed that a 68-year-old woman suffered a ruptured aorta and ruptured liver.<ref name=AviationHerald /> She died on the way to the hospital.<ref name=Reuters16Aug2010CrashesDuringStorm/><ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/> The second fatality was a girl;<ref>\"[http://www.aires.aero/comunicado_06.html Comunicado de Prensa 06] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100909003235/http://www.aires.aero/comunicado_06.html |date=9 September 2010 }}.\" AIRES. Retrieved on 15 September 2010.</ref> she sustained substantial brain damage{{citation needed|date=September 2010}} and died 16 days after the accident.<ref>https://www.elpais.com.co/colombia/companeras-de-colegio-dieron-el-ultimo-adios-a-maria-camila-angarita.html</ref>\n\nOne report stated that the passenger list included six Americans, five Mexicans, four Brazilians, four Ecuadorians and two Germans, the rest being Colombians.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> Another report stated there were three Americans aboard.<ref name=Caracol/> A later report put the number of non-Colombians aboard as 'at least 16'.<ref name=BBCNews17Aug2010AirCrashMiracle/>\n\n== Investigation ==\nColombia's civil aviation authority, [[Special Administrative Unit of Civil Aeronautics]], and the [[Colombian Air Force]] opened an investigation into the accident.<ref name=Eltiempo/> The airport was closed as investigators examined the wreckage.<ref name=Reuters16Aug2010CrashesDuringStorm/> The closure was expected to last until 06:00 on 17 August.<ref name=Eltiempo/>\n\nThe aircraft reportedly crashed in bad weather, while a storm was reported in the area, but not at the airport.<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> The [[METAR]] (aviation routine weather observation message) report in force at the time of the accident indicated that the wind was from the east north east at {{convert|6|kn|km/h mph|abbr=}}, visibility was good and that the runway was wet.<ref group=Notes>Raw data from the [[METAR]] report were: SKSP 160500Z 07006KT 9999 FEW016 SCT200 29/26 A2990=Translated: Gustavo Rojas Pinilla International Airport date: 16th day of the month, time: 0500 zulu/UTC, wind: 070\u00b0 at 6 kt, visibility: 10&nbsp;km or more, few clouds at 1600&nbsp;ft., scattered clouds at 20000&nbsp;ft., temperature 29&nbsp;\u00b0C, dew point 26&nbsp;\u00b0C, altimeter setting (pressure) 29.90 inHg.</ref><ref name=AviationHerald /> The aircraft \"landed in the middle of an intense electrical storm\" according to Colonel Barrero.<ref name=Reuters16Aug2010CrashesDuringStorm/>\n\nPassenger accounts the day after the crash detailed how the approach appeared to have been going normally, with the flight attendants having made the passengers ready for landing, when the crash occurred suddenly and without warning.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/><ref name=ABCNews17Aug2010InsideMiracle/><ref name=BBCNews17Aug2010AirCrashMiracle/> The pilot did not report an emergency to the tower.<ref name=Yahoo17Aug2010WomanDies/> There were conflicting reports over what caused the crash, suggesting that the landing was disrupted after the aircraft was hit by a [[downdraft]], or struck by [[lightning]].<ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/> The pilot said that the aircraft was struck by lightning. Officials refused to comment on the reports of a lightning strike,<ref name=BBC16Aug2010PlaneBreaks/><ref name=CNN16Aug2010JetSplitsApart/><ref name=Eltiempo/> although subsequent research proved that{{specify|date=December 2018}} was not true. No aircraft has had an accident caused by lightning [[LANSA Flight 508|since 1971]]. The airport was not fitted with equipment such as a Doppler radar, used to detect wind shear.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/>\n\nBoth the [[flight recorder|flight data and cockpit voice recorders]] were recovered from the wreckage.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/> Based on the pattern of wreckage, investigators concluded that the aircraft had broken up on impact and not while in the air.<ref name=AP17Aug2010130Survive/>\n\nThe U.S. [[National Transportation Safety Board]] sent a team to support the Colombian-led investigation as representatives of the manufacturer's state.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.ntsb.gov/Pressrel/2010/100816c.html |title=NTSB sending team to assist government of Colombia with today's 737 accident |date=16 August 2010 |publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]] }}</ref>\n\nAlmost one year after the accident, on 15 July 2011, the Security Council of Aeron\u00e1utica Civil concluded that the cause of the accident was the execution of the final approach below the glide path, due to an error of judgment by the crew who believed they were much higher. This is typical of a \"black hole\" illusion, which is experienced during a night approach to a low contrast runway environment surrounded by bright lights, aggravated by heavy rain.<ref name=\"Final report\"/> Aerona\u00fatica Civil recommended retraining of the crew. Although the accident was caused by human error, Aerona\u00fatica representative Colonel Carlos Silva reminded that the purpose of the investigation was not to apportion blame but to prevent aircraft accidents that may occur in the future.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/colombia/otraszonas/ARTICULO-WEB-NEW_NOTA_INTERIOR-9916084.html|title=Error del piloto y mal tiempo, causas del accidente de avi\u00f3n de Aires|date=15 July 2011|work=[[El Tiempo (Colombia)|El Tiempo]]|accessdate=19 January 2013|language=Spanish|trans-title=Pilot error and bad weather, causes of the plane crash in Aires}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Notes}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=AviationHerald>{{cite web |url=http://www.avherald.com/h?article=42fb63a9&opt=0 | title=Accident: Aires B737 at San Andres Island on 16 Aug 2010, landed short of runway and broke up |accessdate=19 August 2010 |date=16 August 2010 |work=Aviation Herald}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Airfleets>{{cite web|url=http://www.airfleets.net/ficheapp/plane-b737ng-32416.htm |title=Boeing 737 Next Gen \u2013 MSN 32416  |publisher=Airfleets |accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Reuters16Aug2010CrashesDuringStorm>{{cite news\n|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idAFTRE67F2AI20100816\n|title=Colombian airliner crashes during storm leaving one dead\n|publisher=Reuters\n|date=16 August 2010\n|accessdate=16 August 2010\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100818183912/https://af.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idAFTRE67F2AI20100816| archivedate= 18 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Eltiempo>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.eltiempo.com/colombia/caribe/accidente-de-avion-en-san-andres_7866340-1\n |title       = Ministro de Transporte descart\u00f3 fallas t\u00e9cnicas de la aeronave que se accident\u00f3 en San Andr\u00e9s\n |publisher   = El Tiempo\n |language    = Spanish\n |accessdate  = 16 August 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120928084901/http://www.eltiempo.com/colombia/caribe/accidente-de-avion-en-san-andres_7866340-1\n |archivedate = 28 September 2012\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Caracol>{{cite web\n|url=http://