36Xv?url=http://www.aerocivil.gov.co/AAeronautica/InvAccidentes/LAccidentes/Accidentes/FINAL%20HK4682%20-%20part%20I.pdf Archive])\n* [http://www.radiosantafe.com/2010/08/16/lista-oficial-de-ocupantes-del-avion-8250-de-aires/ Passenger list] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in Colombia}}\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 2010}}\n{{Portal bar|Aviation|Colombia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aires Flight 8250}}\n[[Category:2010 in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Boeing 737 Next Generation]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 2010]]\n[[Category:Archipelago of San Andr\u00e9s, Providencia and Santa Catalina]]\n[[Category:August 2010 events in South America]]\n", "name_user": "XenithXenaku", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added summary information fromMayday.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AIRES_Flight_8250"}
{"title_page": "2027 Rugby World Cup", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox Rugby World Cup\n| logo         =\n|datefrom=10 September\n|dateto= 23 October\n| nations      = \n| champion     =\n| runnerup     =\n| matches      =\n| attendance   =\n| apm          =\n| top scorer   =\n| preceded by  = [[2023 Rugby World Cup|2023]]\n| succeeded by = [[2031 Rugby World Cup|2031]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2027 Rugby World Cup''' is scheduled to be the eleventh [[Rugby World Cup]].\n\n==Hosting==\n{{See also|Rugby World Cup hosts}}\n\nAs of June 2019, three countries, [[Argentina]], [[Australia]] and [[Russia]], had declared their interest in hosting the 2027 Rugby World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Australia to bid for 2027 Rugby World Cup and 2021 women's tournament |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/dec/13/australia-to-bid-for-2027-rugby-world-cup-and-2021-womens-tournament |work=[[Guardian Australia|The Guardian Australia]] |location= |date=13 December 2017 |access-date=6 June 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rugby.com.au/news/2016/10/04/23/01/argentina-2027-bid |title=Argentina announces 2027 Rugby World Cup bid |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=5 October 2016 |website=[[Rugby Australia|Rugby.com.au]] |publisher= |access-date=6 June 2018}}</ref> There has been speculation that the [[United States]] and [[South Africa]] would announce their interest in hosting the event, however, nothing has been officially announced. \n\n[[World Rugby]] Chairman [[Bill Beaumont]] suggested in late 2018 that the host of the [[Rugby World Cup|World Cup]] following the [[2023 Rugby World Cup|2023]] event in [[France]] could be an emerging nation.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Australia and South Africa could miss out on 2027 Rugby World Cup as Bill Beaumont says another emerging nation could host tournament |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/rugby/rugby-world-cup-2015/australia-and-south-africa-could-miss-out-on-2027-rugby-world-cup-as-bill-beaumont-says-another-emerging-nation-could-host-tournament/news-story/2e4a8573c5d89a3c6b465dd23d064783 |work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports Australia]] |location= |date=20 September 2018 |access-date=2 June 2019 }}</ref> World Rugby CEO Brett Gosper also suggested in 2019 that World Rugby may bid the 2027 and 2031 World Cups together (as they did with England 2015 and Japan 2019), so that they could make \u201ca bolder decision and a traditional decision.\u201d<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1085185/united-states-rugby-world-cup-hosting|title=Rugby World Cup in sights of United States|date=26 September 2019|website=www.insidethegames.biz}}</ref> Gosper further suggested that \u201c2031 could give time for an American bid to be very credible and very strong.\u201d<ref name=\"auto\"/> As of 2019, the hosts for the 2027 and 2031 tournaments are expected to be revealed in 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rugby.com.au/News/2019/10/08/Rugby-World-Cup-Australia-bid-Japan-Cheika-Kerevi?amp=1|title=Australia \"would kill it\" at hosting another Rugby World Cup: Cheika &#124; Rugby.com.au|website=www.rugby.com.au}}</ref>\n\nThe fact that three consecutive World Cups (2015 England, 2019 Japan, and 2023 France) will have occurred in the northern hemisphere makes the southern hemisphere countries considered the favourites.<ref>{{cite news |last=Neville |first=Conor |date=15 November 2017 |title=Why France win was the worst possible result for Ireland |url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/rugby/2017/1115/920299-2023/ |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |location= |access-date=2 June 2019 }}</ref> Relatedly, the fact that the 2023 tournament will be in France makes it unlikely that World Rugby would select a European country to host in 2027.\n\n=== withdrawn bids ===\n\n====Argentina==== \nArgentina have withdrawn from contention of hosting rwc 2027 as of April 16th 2020 (various sources).\n\n=== announced bidders ===\n====Australia====\n[[Rugby Australia]] announced on 13 December 2017 that Australia would bid for the 2027 Rugby World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Australia bidding for 2027 Rugby World Cup |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/australia-bidding-for-2027-rugby-world-cup |work=[[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS News]] |location= |date=13 December 2017 |access-date=2 June 2019 }}</ref> Australia has previously hosted the [[1987 Rugby World Cup]] together with [[New Zealand]], as well as the [[2003 Rugby World Cup]] on its own. If Australia were to host the 2027 Rugby World Cup it would mark 40 years since they hosted the first tournament in 1987.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!colspan=2|[[Sydney]]\n!colspan=2|[[Melbourne]]\n|-\n|[[Stadium Australia]]\n|[[Sydney Football Stadium (2022)]]\n|[[Docklands Stadium]]\n|[[Melbourne Rectangular Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''75,000'''\n|Capacity: '''45,000'''\n|Capacity: '''56,347'''\n|Capacity: '''33,000'''\n|-\n|[[File:State of Origin Game II 2018 (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|\n|[[File:Docklands Stadium, Melbourne (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:2015 A-League Grand Final AAMI Park panorama (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n![[Perth]]\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"8\"| <div style=\"width:400px; border-color:#c6ecff; border-style:solid; border-width:0 38px 25px 12px;\">{{Location map+|Australia  |width=400 |float=center |caption= |places=\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-33.865    |long=151.209444  |position=left    |label='''[[Sydney]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-27.467778 |long=153.028056  |position=top     |label='''[[Brisbane]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-37.813611 |long= 144.963056 |position=right   |label='''[[Melbourne]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-34.928889 |long=138.601111  |position=left    |label='''[[Adelaide]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-31.952222 |long=115.858889  |position=right   |label='''[[Perth]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-28.016667 |long=153.4       |position=bottom\n|label='''[[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]]'''}} \n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-19.256389 |long=146.818333  |position=left    |label='''[[Townsville]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-35.293056 |long=149.126944  |position=left    |label='''[[Canberra]]'''}} \n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-32.916667 |long=151.75      |position=top     |label='''[[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]]'''}}\n}}</div>\n![[Adelaide]]\n|-\n|[[Perth Stadium]]\n|[[Adelaide Oval]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''65,000'''\n|Capacity: '''53,583''' \n|-\n|[[File:E37 Perth Stadium Open Day 099 (cropped).JPG|frameless]]\n|[[File:Adelaide Oval - panoramio (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n![[Brisbane]]\n![[Western Sydney]]\n|-\n|[[Suncorp Stadium]]\n|[[Western Sydney Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''52,500'''\n|Capacity: '''30,000'''\n|-\n|[[File:Suncorp Stadium 22 April 2012 (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:View Inside Western Sydney Stadium on Opening Day (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n![[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]]\n![[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]]\n![[Canberra]]\n![[Townsville]]\n|-\n|[[Newcastle International Sports Centre|Newcastle Stadium]]\n|[[Robina Stadium]]\n|[[Canberra Stadium]]\n|[[North Queensland Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''30,500'''\n|Capacity: '''27,400'''\n|Capacity: '''25,011'''\n|Capacity: '''25,000'''\n|-\n|[[File:Ausgrid Stadium (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:Skilled Park (2008) (cropped).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|[[File:BruceStadium19032005 (cropped).JPG|alt=|frameless]]\n|[[File:QCB Stadium.jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|}\n\n====Russia====\nStanislav Druzhinin, general director of the Russian Rugby Union, at a meeting of the high council on 31 May 2019, said that Russia would apply to hold the 2027 Rugby World Cup. Russia would use the 2018 FIFA World Cup stadiums for the 2027 Rugby World Cup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.americasrugbynews.com/2019/10/06/russia-to-bid-to-host-rwc-2027/|title=Russia To Bid To Host RWC 2027|date=6 October 2019}}</ref> The legacy of the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] will be used to the maximum.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dyachkova |first=Elena |date=31 May 2019 |title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0431\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0442\u044c \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u043a\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u041a\u041c-2027 |trans-title=Russian Rugby Federation will apply to host the 2027 Rugby World Cup |url=https://rsport.ria.ru/20190531/1555157222.html |language=Russian|work=Ria |location= |access-date=2 June 2019 }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Moscow]]\n![[Saint Petersburg]]\n![[Sochi]]\n|-\n|[[Luzhniki Stadium]]\n|[[Otkritie Arena|Spartak Stadium]]\n|[[Krestovsky Stadium]]\n|[[Fisht Olympic Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''81,000'''\n|Capacity: '''44,307'''\n|Capacity: '''64,468'''\n|Capacity: '''47,659'''\n|-\n|[[File:Luzhniki Stadium2.jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:Otkrytiye stadium (Spartak). 30-08-2014.jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:Krestovsky Stadium 2018.jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:Fisht Olympic Stadium 2017.jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n![[Volgograd]]\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"12\" |{{Location map+|European Russia|places={{Location map~ |European Russia |lat_deg=55|lat_min=45|lon_deg=37|lon_min=37|position=left  |label='''[[Moscow]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |European Russia |lat_deg=59|lat_min=58|lon_deg=30|lon_min=13|position=right |label='''{{nowrap|[[Saint Petersburg]]}}'''}}\n{{Location map~ |European Russia |lat_deg=54|lat_min=53|lon_deg=20|lon_min=29|position=right |label='''[[Kaliningrad]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |European Russia |lat_deg=56|lat_min=16|lon_deg=43|lon_min=53|position=top   |label='''[[Nizhny Novgorod]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |European Russia |lat_deg=55|lat_min=49|lon_deg=49|lon_min=09|position=right |label='''[[Kazan]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |European Russia |lat_deg=45|lat_min=02|lon_deg=38|lon_min=99||position=right|label='''[[Krasnodar]]'''}} \n{{Location map~ |European Russia |lat_deg=53|lat_min=14|lon_deg=50|lon_min=16|position=right |label='''[[Samara]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |European Russia |lat_deg=48|lat_min=44|lon_deg=44|lon_min=32|position=top   |label='''[[Volgograd]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |European Russia |lat_deg=54|lat_min=10|lon_deg=45|lon_min=11|position=left  |label='''[[Saransk]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |European Russia |lat_deg=43|lat_min=34|lon_deg=39|lon_min=51|position=left  |label='''[[Sochi]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |European Russia |lat_deg=47|lat_min=14|lon_deg=39|lon_min=43|position=right |label='''{{nowrap|[[Rostov-on-Don]]}}'''}}\n{{Location map~ |European Russia |lat_deg=56|lat_min=50|lon_deg=60|lon_min=35|position=top   |label='''[[Yekaterinburg]]'''}}|width=400|float=center|caption=}}\n![[Kazan]]\n|-\n|[[Volgograd Arena]]\n|[[Kazan Arena]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''45,568'''\n|Capacity: '''45,379'''\n|-\n|[[File:Construction of Volgograd Arena inside 04.jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:Kazan Arena stadium.jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n![[Rostov-on-Don]]\n![[Samara]]\n|-\n|[[Rostov Arena]]\n|[[Cosmos Arena]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''45,000'''\n|Capacity: '''44,918'''\n|-\n|[[File:Rostov Arena.jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:Sweden-England.jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n![[Nizhny Novgorod]]\n![[Saransk]]\n|-\n|[[Nizhny Novgorod Stadium]]\n|[[Mordovia Arena]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''44,899'''\n|Capacity: '''44,442'''\n|-\n|[[File:Nizhny Novgorod Stadium (06 May 2018).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|[[File:Match at Mordovia Arena stadium.jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|-\n![[Kaliningrad]]\n![[Krasnodar]]\n![[Yekaterinburg]]\n![[Krasnoyarsk]]\n|-\n|[[Kaliningrad Stadium]]\n|[[Krasnodar Stadium]]\n|[[Central Stadium (Yekaterinburg)|Central Stadium]]\n|[[Central Stadium (Krasnoyarsk)|Central Stadium]]{{refn|Despite not being included on the map, Central Stadium is located in [[Krasnoyarsk]] in central [[Krasnoyarsk Krai]], which make up one of nine [[Krais of Russia|Krais]], one of eight [[Siberian Federal District|federal districts]], and one of six [[Federal subjects of Russia|federal subjects]] in [[Russia]].|name=\"Central Stadium\"|group=note}}\n|-\n|Capacity: '''35,212'''\n|Capacity: '''35,074'''\n|Capacity: '''35,061'''\n|Capacity: '''15,000'''\n|-\n|[[File:Ser-Swi (1).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|[[File:Krasnodar u19- RMu19 (10).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|[[File:E-burg_asv2019-05_img22_Central_Stadium.jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|[[File:Krasnoyarsk_Central_Stadium.JPG|alt=|frameless]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of the Rugby World Cup]]\n\n==Notes== \n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rugby Union World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World Cup}}\n[[Category:2027 Rugby World Cup|2027]]\n[[Category:2027 in rugby union]]\n[[Category:Rugby World Cup tournaments|2027]]\n[[Category:Scheduled sports events|Rugby World Cup 2027]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox Rugby World Cup\n| logo         =\n|datefrom=10 September\n|dateto= 23 October\n| nations      = \n| champion     =\n| runnerup     =\n| matches      =\n| attendance   =\n| apm          =\n| top scorer   =\n| preceded by  = [[2023 Rugby World Cup|2023]]\n| succeeded by = [[2031 Rugby World Cup|2031]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2027 Rugby World Cup''' is scheduled to be the eleventh [[Rugby World Cup]].\n\n==Hosting==\n{{See also|Rugby World Cup hosts}}\n\nAs of June 2019, three countries, [[Argentina]], [[Australia]] and [[Russia]], had declared their interest in hosting the 2027 Rugby World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Australia to bid for 2027 Rugby World Cup and 2021 women's tournament |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/dec/13/australia-to-bid-for-2027-rugby-world-cup-and-2021-womens-tournament |work=[[Guardian Australia|The Guardian Australia]] |location= |date=13 December 2017 |access-date=6 June 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rugby.com.au/news/2016/10/04/23/01/argentina-2027-bid |title=Argentina announces 2027 Rugby World Cup bid |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=5 October 2016 |website=[[Rugby Australia|Rugby.com.au]] |publisher= |access-date=6 June 2018}}</ref> There has been speculation that the [[United States]] and [[South Africa]] would announce their interest in hosting the event, however, nothing has been officially announced. \n\n[[World Rugby]] Chairman [[Bill Beaumont]] suggested in late 2018 that the host of the [[Rugby World Cup|World Cup]] following the [[2023 Rugby World Cup|2023]] event in [[France]] could be an emerging nation.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Australia and South Africa could miss out on 2027 Rugby World Cup as Bill Beaumont says another emerging nation could host tournament |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/rugby/rugby-world-cup-2015/australia-and-south-africa-could-miss-out-on-2027-rugby-world-cup-as-bill-beaumont-says-another-emerging-nation-could-host-tournament/news-story/2e4a8573c5d89a3c6b465dd23d064783 |work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports Australia]] |location= |date=20 September 2018 |access-date=2 June 2019 }}</ref> World Rugby CEO Brett Gosper also suggested in 2019 that World Rugby may bid the 2027 and 2031 World Cups together (as they did with England 2015 and Japan 2019), so that they could make \u201ca bolder decision and a traditional decision.\u201d<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1085185/united-states-rugby-world-cup-hosting|title=Rugby World Cup in sights of United States|date=26 September 2019|website=www.insidethegames.biz}}</ref> Gosper further suggested that \u201c2031 could give time for an American bid to be very credible and very strong.\u201d<ref name=\"auto\"/> As of 2019, the hosts for the 2027 and 2031 tournaments are expected to be revealed in 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rugby.com.au/News/2019/10/08/Rugby-World-Cup-Australia-bid-Japan-Cheika-Kerevi?amp=1|title=Australia \"would kill it\" at hosting another Rugby World Cup: Cheika &#124; Rugby.com.au|website=www.rugby.com.au}}</ref>\n\nThe fact that three consecutive World Cups (2015 England, 2019 Japan, and 2023 France) will have occurred in the northern hemisphere makes the southern hemisphere countries considered the favourites.<ref>{{cite news |last=Neville |first=Conor |date=15 November 2017 |title=Why France win was the worst possible result for Ireland |url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/rugby/2017/1115/920299-2023/ |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |location= |access-date=2 June 2019 }}</ref> Relatedly, the fact that the 2023 tournament will be in France makes it unlikely that World Rugby would select a European country to host in 2027.\n\n=== withdrawn bids ===\n\n====Argentina==== \nArgentina have withdrew from hosting rwc 2027 as of April 16th 2020 (various sources).\n=== announced bidders ===\n====Australia====\n[[Rugby Australia]] announced on 13 December 2017 that Australia would bid for the 2027 Rugby World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Australia bidding for 2027 Rugby World Cup |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/australia-bidding-for-2027-rugby-world-cup |work=[[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS News]] |location= |date=13 December 2017 |access-date=2 June 2019 }}</ref> Australia has previously hosted the [[1987 Rugby World Cup]] together with [[New Zealand]], as well as the [[2003 Rugby World Cup]] on its own. If Australia were to host the 2027 Rugby World Cup it would mark 40 years since they hosted the first tournament in 1987.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!colspan=2|[[Sydney]]\n!colspan=2|[[Melbourne]]\n|-\n|[[Stadium Australia]]\n|[[Sydney Football Stadium (2022)]]\n|[[Docklands Stadium]]\n|[[Melbourne Rectangular Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''75,000'''\n|Capacity: '''45,000'''\n|Capacity: '''56,347'''\n|Capacity: '''33,000'''\n|-\n|[[File:State of Origin Game II 2018 (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|\n|[[File:Docklands Stadium, Melbourne (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:2015 A-League Grand Final AAMI Park panorama (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n![[Perth]]\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"8\"| <div style=\"width:400px; border-color:#c6ecff; border-style:solid; border-width:0 38px 25px 12px;\">{{Location map+|Australia  |width=400 |float=center |caption= |places=\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-33.865    |long=151.209444  |position=left    |label='''[[Sydney]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-27.467778 |long=153.028056  |position=top     |label='''[[Brisbane]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-37.813611 |long= 144.963056 |position=right   |label='''[[Melbourne]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-34.928889 |long=138.601111  |position=left    |label='''[[Adelaide]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-31.952222 |long=115.858889  |position=right   |label='''[[Perth]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-28.016667 |long=153.4       |position=bottom\n|label='''[[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]]'''}} \n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-19.256389 |long=146.818333  |position=left    |label='''[[Townsville]]'''}}\n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-35.293056 |long=149.126944  |position=left    |label='''[[Canberra]]'''}} \n{{Location map~ |Australia |lat=-32.916667 |long=151.75      |position=top     |label='''[[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]]'''}}\n}}</div>\n![[Adelaide]]\n|-\n|[[Perth Stadium]]\n|[[Adelaide Oval]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''65,000'''\n|Capacity: '''53,583''' \n|-\n|[[File:E37 Perth Stadium Open Day 099 (cropped).JPG|frameless]]\n|[[File:Adelaide Oval - panoramio (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n![[Brisbane]]\n![[Western Sydney]]\n|-\n|[[Suncorp Stadium]]\n|[[Western Sydney Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''52,500'''\n|Capacity: '''30,000'''\n|-\n|[[File:Suncorp Stadium 22 April 2012 (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:View Inside Western Sydney Stadium on Opening Day (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|-\n![[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]]\n![[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]]\n![[Canberra]]\n![[Townsville]]\n|-\n|[[Newcastle International Sports Centre|Newcastle Stadium]]\n|[[Robina Stadium]]\n|[[Canberra Stadium]]\n|[[North Queensland Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''30,500'''\n|Capacity: '''27,400'''\n|Capacity: '''25,011'''\n|Capacity: '''25,000'''\n|-\n|[[File:Ausgrid Stadium (cropped).jpg|frameless]]\n|[[File:Skilled Park (2008) (cropped).jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|[[File:BruceStadium19032005 (cropped).JPG|alt=|frameless]]\n|[[File:QCB Stadium.jpg|alt=|frameless]]\n|}\n\n====Russia====\nStanislav Druzhinin, general director of the Russian Rugby Union, at a meeting of the high council on 31 May 2019, said that Russia would apply to hold the 2027 Rugby World Cup. Russia would use the 2018 FIFA World Cup stadiums for the 2027 Rugby World Cup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.americasrugbynews.com/2019/10/06/russia-to-bid-to-host-rwc-2027/|title=Russia To Bid To Host RWC 2027|date=6 October 2019}}</ref> The legacy of the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] will be used to the maximum.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dyachkova |first=Elena |date=31 May 2019 |title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0431\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0442\u044c \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u043a\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u041a\u041c-2027 |trans-title=Russian Rugby Federation will apply to host the 2027 Rugby World Cup |url=https://rsport.ria.ru/20190531/1555157222.html |language=Russian|work=Ria |location= |access-date=2 June 2019 }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Moscow]]\n![[Saint Petersburg]]\n![[Sochi]]\n|-\n|[[Luzhniki Stadium]]\n|[[Otkritie Arena|Spartak Stadium]]\n|[[Krestovsky Stadium]]\n|[[Fisht Olympic Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''81,000'''\n|Capacity: '''44,307'''\n|Capacity: '''64,468'''\n|Capa